Obeying Jesus‚Äô command taught me several powerful truths we experience when we pray for people who have hurt us: 1. Prayer shields our hearts from bitterness. It gives us a verbal outlet for our pain, a way to begin releasing our resentment to God. It prevents righteous anger and real hurt from twisting into damaging bitterness. 2. Prayer humbles us. It reminds us that even when we have been hurt, we are imperfect and need grace too. It may even help us to consider the conflict from the other person‚Äôs perspective. 3. Prayer helps us resist the temptation to seek revenge. It reminds us that God loves justice and that we can trust Him to defend and protect us. 4. Prayer gives us peace while we wait for resolution. Praying strengthens our relationship with God during our relational conflict. We trust that God is working even when we can‚Äôt see or understand all He is doing. If you‚Äôre embroiled in a conflict, wrestling with bitterness, or feeling hurt or confused by a strained relationship, Jesus‚Äô encouragement to pray for your enemy may provide the protection your heart needs. You can pray about your situation, and pray for the person with whom you are in conflict, every day ‚Äî even multiple times a day. Feeling wounded by a friend‚Äôs refusal to accept your apology? You can pray about that. Feeling afraid she may hurt more people if she doesn‚Äôt change? You can pray about that. Longing to attempt reconciliation but not sure the other person will even speak to you? You can pray about that. We can pray about all of it. God welcomes our requests, and He longs to help His children find forgiveness and unity (John 17:20-23). It takes time, but when we commit to persistently praying for those who offend us, we give God the chance to work on their hearts ‚Äî and ours. -Elizabeth Laing Thompson, Writer How has prayer protected your heart when you‚Äôve been hurt?

Some people cannot stay out of conflict or trouble. Every time you turn around, they are in a squabble or fight with someone else. If you help them get out of one mess, they quickly get into another. They have hot tempers and unruled spirits, so there is no hope for them. They will have a life of trouble, ruin their relationships, and then die lonely. The lessons are simple. First, if you do not rule your anger, God and men will punish you for your temper. A wise man will confess his angry spirit, beg God to help him, and obey the proverbs about anger. Second, if you help a person with a bad temper, you will be helping him again next month, for he cannot learn to get along with others. His selfish spirit and hot temper will explode again against some little offence, real or perceived. Neither anger nor a temper is noble. It is not a sign of manliness or authority. It is not the evidence of a strong man ‚Äì it is the proof of a weak fool (Eccl 7:9). A great man rules his spirit and controls his anger; fools are ruled by their spirits and controlled by their anger. Wrath is blinding and binding, so that helping a quick-tempered man out of trouble caused by his anger will not protect him for long; he will sin again by anger very soon. Wrath is violent anger. It is the emotional volcano that erupts in a fool‚Äôs heart when he is offended or does not get his way. It is a terrible evil. It leads to many sins of thought, speech, and action. Jesus knew it was at the root of murder, so He condemned unjustified anger as murder in God‚Äôs sight (Matt 5:21-22). A man with a temper will be guilty of many sins (Pr 10:12; 12:16; 14:17; 15:18; 17:19; 22:24-25; 26:21; 29:22; 30:33). If a man has not learned to rule his spirit, you must rescue him over and over again from the trouble his anger causes (Pr 27:3). He is a burden to deal with, because you must be constantly covering or correcting his foolish passions. Delivering him today from a mess his anger caused will not help you tomorrow ‚Äì he will do it again. A wise man avoids angry men, because they are mostly trouble as friends (Pr 13:20; 21:24; 22:24-25; 29:22). Learn to hate anger, for it is unmanageable (Pr 27:3-4). It is a work of your sinful flesh and old man, not the new man of a child of God (Eph 4:31; Col 3:8). Slow your passions down, especially anger (Pr 16:32). Glorious men postpone anger (Pr 19:11). Only fools let it fly (Ec 7:9). Learn to get over anger quickly and end conflicts, for unresolved anger gives place to the devil (Eph 4:26-27). Exalt mercy instead (Pr 3:3; 21:3; Micah 6:8). Learn to love, which is God‚Äôs greatest grace toward you, and the greatest grace you can show others (I Cor 13:4-7,13). It is the greatest evidence of eternal life and God‚Äôs presence in your life. Love teaches and empowers you to bear, endure, and suffer for a long time; it teaches you to not be easily provoked. God is love. Do you know God (I John 4:7-8,16)? If you know God, you will show love rather than anger to others in life. https://letgodbetrue.com/proverbs/index/chapter-19/proverbs-19-19/

Today, President Abdel Fattah El-Sisi met with General Michael Kurilla, Commander, U.S. Central Command. The meeting was also attended by Minister of Defense and Military Production General Mohamed Zaki. The Spokesman for the Presidency said both sides stressed keenness to strengthen the strategic partnership between Egypt and the United States and to intensify the ongoing cooperation and coordination in various fields, especially military and security, in light of their importance to support efforts to restore security and stability and consolidate peace in the Middle East. The meeting reviewed a number of issues of common interest, particularly the developments in the Gaza Strip. The President outlined Egypt‚Äôs efforts for de-escalation, stressing the importance of the international community' concerted efforts to contain the crisis and stop its escalation in dangerous directions, and shifting to the approach of reviving the peace path based on the solution of two states that live side by side in peace and security, taking into account the danger of the security consequences of this conflict from extending to the entire region. The humanitarian situation in the Gaza Strip was also discussed. President El-Sisi stressed the importance of continuing to deliver humanitarian aid to the Palestinian people in the Strip in a sustainable manner, as a top priority, in light of the deteriorating humanitarian conditions in the Strip.

Some people cannot stay out of conflict or trouble. Every time you turn around, they are in a squabble or fight with someone else. If you help them get out of one mess, they quickly get into another. They have hot tempers and unruled spirits, so there is no hope for them. They will have a life of trouble, ruin their relationships, and then die lonely. The lessons are simple. First, if you do not rule your anger, God and men will punish you for your temper. A wise man will confess his angry spirit, beg God to help him, and obey the proverbs about anger. Second, if you help a person with a bad temper, you will be helping him again next month, for he cannot learn to get along with others. His selfish spirit and hot temper will explode again against some little offence, real or perceived. Neither anger nor a temper is noble. It is not a sign of manliness or authority. It is not the evidence of a strong man ‚Äì it is the proof of a weak fool (Eccl 7:9). A great man rules his spirit and controls his anger; fools are ruled by their spirits and controlled by their anger. Wrath is blinding and binding, so that helping a quick-tempered man out of trouble caused by his anger will not protect him for long; he will sin again by anger very soon. Wrath is violent anger. It is the emotional volcano that erupts in a fool‚Äôs heart when he is offended or does not get his way. It is a terrible evil. It leads to many sins of thought, speech, and action. Jesus knew it was at the root of murder, so He condemned unjustified anger as murder in God‚Äôs sight (Matt 5:21-22). A man with a temper will be guilty of many sins (Pr 10:12; 12:16; 14:17; 15:18; 17:19; 22:24-25; 26:21; 29:22; 30:33). If a man has not learned to rule his spirit, you must rescue him over and over again from the trouble his anger causes (Pr 27:3). He is a burden to deal with, because you must be constantly covering or correcting his foolish passions. Delivering him today from a mess his anger caused will not help you tomorrow ‚Äì he will do it again. A wise man avoids angry men, because they are mostly trouble as friends (Pr 13:20; 21:24; 22:24-25; 29:22). Learn to hate anger, for it is unmanageable (Pr 27:3-4). It is a work of your sinful flesh and old man, not the new man of a child of God (Eph 4:31; Col 3:8). Slow your passions down, especially anger (Pr 16:32). Glorious men postpone anger (Pr 19:11). Only fools let it fly (Ec 7:9). Learn to get over anger quickly and end conflicts, for unresolved anger gives place to the devil (Eph 4:26-27). Exalt mercy instead (Pr 3:3; 21:3; Micah 6:8). Learn to love, which is God‚Äôs greatest grace toward you, and the greatest grace you can show others (I Cor 13:4-7,13). It is the greatest evidence of eternal life and God‚Äôs presence in your life. Love teaches and empowers you to bear, endure, and suffer for a long time; it teaches you to not be easily provoked. God is love. Do you know God (I John 4:7-8,16)? If you know God, you will show love rather than anger to others in life. https://letgodbetrue.com/proverbs/index/chapter-19/proverbs-19-19/

VICE ADMIRAL GAVAN IS THE 30TH PCG COMMANDANT üáµüá≠ Department of Transportation (DOTr) Secretary Jaime Bautista announces the appointment of CG VICE ADMIRAL RONNIE GIL LATORILLA GAVAN as the 30th Philippine Coast Guard (PCG) Commandant during the Change of Command Ceremony at the National Headquarters, Port Area, Manila, today, 19 October 2023. In his speech, the Transportation Secretary expressed his trust and confidence that CG Vice Admiral Gavan would efficiently lead the PCG in implementing the "White Hull Approach" towards upholding maritime security and safety in the country's exclusive economic zones. "Admiral Art was hailed for his innate peace mindset that steered the country away from any deterioration in the volatile situation at the West Philippine Sea," DOTr Secretary Bautista said. "My belief that Vice Admiral Ronnie Gavan will do the same is anchored on his record of shifting to the 'White Hull Approach' when securing our maritime borders and his introduction of female radio operators, called 'Angels of the Sea,' as a way of diffusing tension during sea conflict," he furthered. Moreover, the Transportation Secretary emphasized President Ferdinand Bongbong Marcos Jr's directives to the PCG during its 122nd founding anniversary as it moved forward to provide better public service to the Filipino nation. "I expect the PCG to provide steadfast service and dedication to duty during times of calamity; uphold our country's maritime security and promote our maritime rights; do its part in fighting smuggling; protect our marine environment; and secure the safety of our fishermen when pursuing their means of livelihood," DOTr Secretary Bautista highlighted. "The Department of Transportation firmly stands with you in your plans and efforts to improve, expand, and modernize your capabilities and services so you can level up your efforts at securing the welfare of our people and our nation," he concluded. The Chief Executive chose CG Vice Admiral Gavan among five recommended candidates to take over the Coast Guard helm following the retirement of CG Admiral Artemio Abu after over 35 years of public service on the same date. Before the said appointment, CG Vice Admiral Gavan served as the PCG's Deputy Commandant for Administration. He was also instrumental in training and capacity-building female Coast Guardians as radio operators dubbed "Angels of the Sea" on board PCG vessels patrolling the West Philippine Sea (WPS). The 30th PCG Commandant is a proud member of the Philippine Military Academy (PMA) Maalab Class of 1993. The Gambia Government‚Äôs statement on the Gaza- Israel conflict Government of the Republic of The Gambia joins the International Community including United Nations (UN), Organization of Islamic Cooperation (OIC), The African Union (AU) and others in vehemently condemning the Israeli Military operations in Gaza for almost two weeks including stoppage of electricity, water, food aid, medical supplies, fuel and the indiscriminate bombing of Al-Ahli Baptist Hospital in Gaza where over 500 innocent Palestinians were killed mostly women, children, the disabled and sick patients. Taking into cognizance the fact that Palestinians have for long been fighting for their legitimate and inalienable rights for self-determination for over 75 years without any success; and given the usurpation of their territories and freedoms by the Occupying Power, the State of Israel, their situation became so dire that utter desperation resulted in this unfortunate war in Gaza. The Government of The Gambia calls for an unconditional ceasefire and the release of all hostages to prevent more bloodshed and the proposed invasion of Gaza which could result not only in more deaths and destruction but also in forcibly displacing Palestinian citizens in Gaza and the West Bank and in doing so build more Israeli settlements in those areas. The Government of the Gambia further appeals to the International Community to compel the Occupying Power to abide by the tenets of the Peace process, International Law, International Humanitarian Law and UN Security Council Resolutions. Failure to do so is bound to prolong the conflict, cause further instability and diminish the chances fora resolution of this conflict. The Government of The Gambia, given that Israeli Military aggression is used as an instrument of collective punishment causing huge loss of life, property and injuries on both sides since the occupation of Palestine in 1948, calls for an International Peace Conference for a permanent and durable solution to this very protracted Palestinian problem. The Government of The Gambia considers that: the best option for a peaceful settlement of this dispute between the two parties is not a military one but a comprehensive Peace Accord based on the "Two-Party Solution" guaranteeing both States their legitimate and inalienable rights to full sovereignty and self-determination. The Government of The Gambia, in this context, reaffirms its support for the Palestinian people to regain their legitimate national rights, as recognized by the International Community through its recognition of a State of Palestine within the borders of June 4th, 1967, with Al-Quds Al- Shareef as its Capital as indicated in all relevant UN, OIC and AU Resolutions. On behalf of H.E. The President of the Republic of The Gambia Mr. Adama Barrow, The Government and People of The Gambia express deepest condolences for the tragic loss of life and property on both sides and wish all those injured speedy recovery and pray that this tragedy which continues to unfold before our own eyes will soon cease and never be repeated again. "What if usa ka adlaw mahibaw'an nalang nimu nga KABIT ra diay ka? What would you do? STAY OR LET GO?" Good day:) Ako diay si Lyn. 22yrs.old. Taga Negros Occidental pero nagtrabaho ko diri karun sa Cebu. Nakahunahuna lang ko nga mo share sa akong love story way back 2015. 17yrs old pako atong mga panahona. HI diay sa mga makarelate diha:) Sa dili, mas maayo:) Year 2015 nagsugod nakug trabaho sa edad nga 17. Wa kapadayun sa skwela kay lagi financial problem. Nagtrabaho ko sa Bacolod and there I met Chan. Tricycle driver. 21yrs old sya that time. Nanguyab sya naku. 2weeks after akoa syang gisugot kay lagi nakita naku iyang sincerity. Dali ra ba? Maybe dali ra, saon man gud. Pafall man si dong Chan. Ug kani laging dali ratang mafall. Buotan man sad sya gud sa akong nakita. Sa nanguyab pa sya ginahatagan ko nyag pagkaon para daw dili ko mapasmo. He even gave me phone pag 1st monthsarry namu. Permi sya gaadto sa akong gitrabahuan para daw maka sure sya nga safe rako. Sweet kaayo sya nga pagkauyab. Tanang pagcare iyang gihatag naku. Gentleman kaayo sya. Mapinanggaon. Dili mapride. Kana bitawng kung masuko ka mangita dayun syag way para maulian ka?:) Everyday naay long sweet message.‚ù§Ô∏è Komportable kaayo ko pag-abot sa iyaha. Kana bitawng sure najud kaayo ka nya kay nafeel nimu nga safety kaayo ka sa iyaha?:) Tanang gipangita sa usa ka babaye naa na niya. Ipafeel nya nimu nga priority kaayo ka para nya. Nga importanti ka! Ug labaw sa tanan ginapafeel nya nga di sya komportable pag wala ka. Happy kaayo ko sa among relasyon. Kanang feeling nga mura kag naas HEAVEN pag naa sya nga imung kauban?:) He's the first one nga mihatag ug buwak nga tinuod sa akoa. Ug kay first time lagi hala namula man hinuon ko naa pay mga kauban nga sigig ingun ug UY KASWEET! YUDIII!üòÖ Makaingun kog PERFECT RELATIONSHIP najud ni. Nga PERFECT MATCH najud mi. One day, around 12am, mitext sya nakug HI. Nabag'uhan ko kay anang mga time ma dili nana sya mutext naku ug usa pa never syang gatext ug HI naku since naging kami. One text is a long sweet message jud na permi. (CONVO) CHAN: HI? ME: Hello? Himala lagi mata paka? Unsa naman ning orasa? Katug na diha. CHAN: Hmmmm, ayaw nag reply diri nga #. Kuhaon lang naku imung # ug mutext rako nimu. Iyaha ning ig-agaw. Nakitext rako. Naa man sya diri natug sa amo gud. (Taud¬≤ naay mitext unknown#): "PWEDE KO MAKIGKITA NIMU? IMPORTANTI LANG"! Mao na ang text sa babaye. Ug ambot ba nganong misugot man sad ko dayun bisan wako kaila atu nya. Pagkaugma nakigkita jud ko nya. Ug sa meeting place, naghuwat ko nyag mga pila ka minutes. Naay miabot nga usa ka babaye. Buntis. Minug anak na. Ug murag naa syay gipangita. Pawala lang sad ko kay naghuwat raman ko sa akong kakita nga mutext naku kung naa naba sya. Ug sa dihang iya kung giduol kay iyaha diay kong nabantayan nga murag naa sad koy gipangita. SIYA diay akong gikatext. Ug nagstorya mi. Didto akong nahibaw'an nga ka live-in partner diay sya sa akong uyab. Dugay na diay kaayo sila nga nag ipon. 14 pa daw sya nag ipon na sila. Ug ingun nya, okay ra daw nya. Naanad na daw sya nga permi sya cheatan ni Chan. Gisakitan man daw sya pero gikinahanglan daw nyang maging strong para sa ilang anak. Dili daw sya gusto nga mawad'an ug amahan iyang anak nga iyang gibuntis. Wala ko makabantay nga mitulo na diay akong luha samtang daghan na kaayo syag giistorya. Ang uban wala naku makabati kay nabungol naku sa akong mga nahibaw'an. Ug giingnan ko ni Mae(live-in partner ni Chan) nga dili daw ko dapat muhilak. Kay si Chan daw dili deserving sa akong mga luha. Ug didto mihilak ko pag ayo. Paano ni Chan nakaya nga mu cheat ni Mae? Buotan man sya ug masinabtanun. Siguro kung uban pato kalkag ng buhok naku. Ingun man gud sya nga kahibaw daw sya nga wako kahibaw nga naay ka live-in si Chan just like sa other woman ni Chan sauna. Sakit nga murag galisud kog tuo nga sa akong edad nga 17, without knowing usa na diay ko ka KABIT?! Miuli ko ug nakigbuwag ko ni Chan through phone. Dili pa unta sya musugot kay mas love daw ko nya ug bata ra daw iyang gusto sa iyang ka livein. Kay wala na daw syay gugma ni Mae. Mituo ko ug wako mipadayug buwag nya. Nabuta ko sa gugma. Nanumpa ko nga never naku mutunob sa BACOLOD nga gitawag nilag CITY OF SMILE kay para naku BACOLOD is CITY OF CRY! Wala naku gipakita sa akong ginikanan ang akong dakong kapakyasan nga nahimo:( Maghilak ko patago. Wala ko gashare ni bisan kinsa kung kumusta na ba akong kasingkasing. Kung okay na ba ko o dili pa! While loathe to add one more uninformed voice to the cacophony, I am compelled to contribute my own sorrow to the collective mourning of lost Israeli and Palestinian lives, lost freedom, lost hope, lost intact families, lost basic human rights, lost necessities to even survive. I can‚Äôt imagine what it has been like to live in an occupied land for almost four generations. I can‚Äôt imagine what it is like to have your children kidnapped. I can‚Äôt imagine having my street bombed. I can‚Äôt imagine having my water and food supply cut off with my babies in the house. I can‚Äôt imagine losing my neighbors to a terrorist attack. I can‚Äôt imagine living inside a conflict that is centuries old. I can‚Äôt imagine 1000 dead children in a day. I can‚Äôt imagine getting my wounded loved one to a hospital only to have it bombed. I can‚Äôt help but think like a mother. Ordinary citizens are not the government. Regular neighbors are not the terrorist organization. Almost all of us who exist in the world are just daughters and sons and moms and dads and grandmas and grandpas and aunts and uncles, innocents, all. We are just friends and community members. We want the same things: basic freedom, safety, and the possibility of goodness for our families. When I think about how many Palestinian and Israeli mothers are going to bed tonight having lost their children, terrified of more violence, just normal people in normal towns, I weep. We aren‚Äôt the lawmakers, the legislators, the ambassadors, or the power brokers. Nor are we the terrorists, the kidnappers, the murderers, or the abusers. Also notably, we aren‚Äôt the pundits, analysts, experts, or strategists. We are just the ordinary global neighbors of the ordinary people of Palestine and Israel, and our tool is compassion. I wish with all my heart for stabilization, liberation, safety, and the end of war for our neighbors. I wish for free people living on free land. I wish all moms could put their babies to bed tonight without fear. Animals are always the forgotten victims in war ‚Äì abandoned in their homes or left to struggle for survival on the streets. We are a community of compassionate animal lovers, and we thank you for supporting our cause and being a voice for the voiceless. Through your support, we've sent funds to four dedicated, brave organizations on the ground, and this is what we know so far: Let the Animals Live (LTAL) in Israel tirelessly collaborates with the military to distribute pet food and rescue over 250 cats and dogs, many with severe injuries, in high-risk areas. Sulala Animal Rescue (SAR) in Gaza is sheltering 400 dogs and 130 cats, with numerous others on the streets, as they bravely risked their lives to rescue pets and their owners despite evacuation orders for 1 million residents in Gaza. Starting Over Sanctuary (SOS) in Israel has taken in over 80 abandoned cats, dogs, donkeys, and horses from conflict areas and urgently needs funds for food and medical bills, having also delivered one ton of food for trapped cats in war zones. Animal Environment Association (AEA) in Bethlehem, Palestine, is dedicated to the well-being of over 100 animals who urgently need food, water, essential medicines, and warm blankets. Our rescue vehicles are on the ground, rushing to feed, evacuate, and treat as many helpless animal victims as possible! The Middle East Problem, It's Not Complex "When I did my graduate studies at the Middle East Institute at Columbia University‚Äôs School of International Affairs, I took many courses on the question of the Middle East conflict. Semester after semester, we studied the Middle East conflict as if it was the most complex conflict in the world -- when in fact, it is probably the easiest conflict in the world to explain. It may be the hardest to solve, but it is the easiest to explain. In a nutshell, it‚Äôs this: One side wants the other side dead. Israel wants to exist as a Jewish state and to live in peace. Israel also recognizes the right of Palestinians to have their own state and to live in peace. The problem, however, is that most Palestinians and many other Muslims and Arabs, do not recognize the right of the Jewish state of Israel to exist. This has been true since 1947, when the United Nations voted to divide the land called Palestine into a Jewish state and an Arab state. The Jews accepted the United Nations partition but no Arab or any other Muslim country accepted it. When British rule ended on May 15, 1948, the armies of all the neighboring Arab states -- Lebanon, Syria, Iraq, Transjordan, and Egypt -- attacked the one-day old state of Israel in order to destroy it. But, to the world‚Äôs surprise, the little Jewish state survived. Then it happened again. In 1967, the dictator of Egypt, Gamal Abdel Nasser, announced his plan, in his words, ‚Äúto destroy Israel.‚Äù He placed Egyptian troops on Israel‚Äôs border, and armies of surrounding Arab countries were also mobilized to attack. However, Israel preemptively attacked Egypt and Syria. Israel did not attack Jordan, and begged Jordan‚Äôs king not to join the war. But he did. And only because of that did Israel take control of Jordanian land, specifically the ‚ÄúWest Bank‚Äù of the Jordan River. Shortly after the war, the Arab states went to Khartoum, Sudan and announced their famous three ‚ÄúNo‚Äôs: ‚ÄúNo recognition, no peace, and no negotiations,‚Äù What was Israel supposed to do? Well, one thing Israel did, a little more than a decade later, in 1978, was to give the entire Sinai Peninsula -- an area of land bigger than Israel itself, and with oil -- back to Egypt because Egypt, under new leadership, signed a peace agreement with Israel. So, Israel gave land for the promise of peace with Egypt, and it has always been willing to do the same thing with the Palestinians. All the Palestinians have ever had to do is recognize Israel as a Jewish state and promise to live in peace with it. But when Israel has proposed trading land for peace -- as it did in 2000 when it agreed to give the Palestinians a sovereign state in more than 95% of the West Bank and all of Gaza -- the Palestinian leadership rejected the offer, and instead responded by sending waves of suicide terrorists into Israel. Meanwhile, Palestinian radio, television, and school curricula remain filled with glorification of terrorists, demonization of Jews, and the daily repeated message that Israel should cease to exist. So it‚Äôs not hard to explain the Middle-East dispute. One side wants the other dead. The motto of Hamas, the Palestinian rulers of Gaza, is: ‚ÄúWe love death as much as the Jews love life.‚Äù There are 22 Arab states in the world -- stretching from the Atlantic Ocean to the Indian Ocean. There is one ‚ÄúJewish State‚Äù in the world. And it is about the size of New Jersey. In fact, tiny El Salvador is larger than Israel. Finally, think about these two questions: If, tomorrow, Israel laid down its arms and announced, ‚ÄúWe will fight no more,‚Äù what would happen? And if the Arab countries around Israel laid down their arms and announced ‚ÄúWe will fight no more,‚Äù what would happen? In the first case there would be an immediate destruction of the state of Israel and the mass murder of its Jewish population. In the second case, there would be peace the next day. As I said at the outset, it is a simple problem to describe: one side wants the other dead -- and if it didn‚Äôt, there would be peace. Please remember this: There has never been a state in the geographic area known as Palestine that was not Jewish. Israel is the third Jewish state to exist in that area. There was never an Arab state, never a Palestinian state, never a Muslim or any other state. That‚Äôs the issue: why can‚Äôt the one Jewish state the size of El Salvador be allowed to exist? That is the Middle-East problem. I‚Äôm Dennis Prager."

**FIELD DAY** Starring Rachel Boston and Benjamin Ayres, with Carmel Amit and Shannon Chan-Kent ***SPOILER ALERT*** Jen (Boston) is a single mom who‚Äôs new in town. At her daughter‚Äôs school, she meets charming PE teacher Dan (Benjamin Ayres), as well as two moms, Marissa (Amit) and Kelly (Chan-Kent). The three women are roped into signing up for the field day planning committee by a manipulative PTO president, Suzanne (Jocelyn Gauthier). Dan offers Jen his assistance, and the two develop an attraction. But Jen, still mourning the loss of her husband, flip-flops over whether she‚Äôs ready to date Dan, and Dan is pessimistic that any romance can ever end happily. Meanwhile, the women‚Äôs plans for a successful field day are threatened by Suzanne‚Äôs sabotage and some foul weather. **PROS** *The leads.* Rachel Boston is a versatile actress who elevates every movie she‚Äôs in, and *Field Day* is no exception. She‚Äôs great in comic roles as well as dramatic ones, and here, Boston had the opportunity to play both. Opposite Ayres, who also shone in this movie, she was a delight. Their banter was playful and clever, and I instantly felt a strong sync between their characters, Jen and Dan. The two had many great scenes together, including a wonderfully honest first date. When their conversation shifted from joking around to serious matters‚ÄîDan getting dumped by the woman he was about to propose to, and the heart-wrenching death of Jen‚Äôs husband‚Äîthey felt as if they‚Äôd shared too much of the wrong sort of information for a first date, and they joked awkwardly about it being the worst first date ever. The scene was full of mixed emotions; what began as fun and flirtatious morphed into a baring of souls that made each of them uncomfortable, and they admitted that discomfort. Jen and Dan‚Äôs hesitation to get involved with each other, in spite of their undeniable attraction, was beautifully conveyed by Boston and Ayres. *A tear-jerking scene.* Get out the Kleenex. After the date was over and Jen concluded she wasn‚Äôt ready for romance, her mother gave her a video that her late husband, Nate (Matt Clarke), had made in case Jen felt stuck and couldn‚Äôt move on after he passed away. Nate‚Äôs video showed how perfectly in tune he and Jen had been with each other. He anticipated what her responses would be to what he was saying, joking about the Live, Love, Laugh sign, for instance, which he knew she‚Äôd find cheesy. But most importantly, he urged her to continue living and to seek happiness. The video blended poignancy with humour, and it was exactly what Jen needed to see before she could embrace the possibility of a future with Dan. *A women‚Äôs buddy movie.* The friendship between the moms was as important as Jen and Dan‚Äôs budding relationship. All three moms were different in terms of personality and background; Jen was a down-to-earth web designer, Marissa a tightly wound workaholic lawyer, and Kelly a bubbly social media star. Yet despite these differences, and their bickering, they became good pals during the course of planning for field day. Many of the film‚Äôs liveliest moments came from the scenes between the women‚Äîfor example, the pumpkin baking competition in which they botched their cake, and the pop-up bar dance scene in which they let loose. And the moms supported each other in overcoming their issues: Jen‚Äôs reluctance to date, Marissa‚Äôs difficulty in relaxing and asking for help, and Kelly‚Äôs inability to just be herself. It was an enjoyable depiction of female friendship that allowed for the reality of some conflict. **CONS** *A couple of stereotypical characters.* Though I mostly liked this film, and I have no doubt that Shannon Chan-Kent is a capable actress, I found her character, Kelly, to be annoying for too much of *Field Day*. It‚Äôs not the first time Hallmark has portrayed influencers in their movies, and the personality type isn‚Äôt appealing. They're always shown as overly perky, superficial, and self-absorbed, obsessed with posting every moment of their lives. Kelly was no exception. At least the source of Kelly‚Äôs phoniness became clear: her online friends were so valuable to her because she associated friendship in real life with being hurt. And at least she gradually became open to exposing her real self. The bully of the story, Suzanne, was also a stereotype‚Äîall smiles on the surface, but underneath that, twisting the knife. Although Suzanne was a minor character, it would have been refreshing if she hadn‚Äôt been so one-dimensional. My grade for **Field Day**: B+

"Gulliver's Travels" by Jonathan Swift is a satirical novel published in 1726. It tells the story of Lemuel Gulliver's voyages to various fantastical lands, including Lilliput, Brobdingnag, Laputa, and the land of the Houyhnhnms. The novel is renowned for its sharp satire and hidden meanings, often criticizing various aspects of society and humanity. Here are a few key themes in "Gulliver's Travels": 1. **Political Satire**: The book satirizes the political landscape of Swift's time. For instance, the conflict between the tiny Lilliputians and the giant Brobdingnagians can be seen as a commentary on the petty disputes among European nations. 2. **Social Critique**: Swift uses the differences between the societies Gulliver encounters to critique various aspects of British society, such as the legal system, government corruption, and the role of the monarchy. 3. **Human Nature**: Gulliver's encounters with different societies highlight the flaws in human nature. The Houyhnhnms, a rational horse-like species, are contrasted with the Yahoos, a degenerate and brutish human-like species, emphasizing the dark aspects of humanity. 4. **Religious and Philosophical Critique**: Swift uses the Laputians and their obsession with theoretical knowledge to criticize the over-intellectualization of society. The Struldbrugs represent the idea of immortality as a curse, critiquing the pursuit of eternal life. 5. **Colonialism and Imperialism**: Gulliver's travels can also be seen as a reflection on the British Empire's expansion and colonialism. His experiences with the Lilliputians and the Houyhnhnms touch on the theme of European imperialism. 6. **Human Size**: The changing scale of Gulliver throughout the book may symbolize the relativity of power and perspective, highlighting how one's status in society can shift based on circumstances. In "Gulliver's Travels," Swift employs allegory, irony, and symbolism to convey his critical views on politics, society, and human nature. The hidden meanings and satirical elements in the book continue to make it a rich source for analysis and interpretation.

Inzamam-ul-Haq, the former Pakistan cricket captain, is reportedly considering stepping down from his role as chief selector due to disagreements with the Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB). Sources suggest that Inzamam is dissatisfied with the appointment of Shahid Anwar as the head coach of the U19 men's team, as he had advocated for former Pakistan cricketer Mohammad Yousaf to be given the position. This is not the first instance of conflict between Inzamam and the PCB, as they have had differences in the past as well. Recently, Inzamam had signed a contract worth Rs2.5 million per month with the PCB. However, the PCB has refuted these claims, with a spokesperson stating that Inzamam had actively participated in the selection process for the U19 men's team and the women's A team, and they had no knowledge of any discord between Inzamam and the board. Earlier in the month, Inzamam was appointed as the chairman of the Junior Men's Cricket Selection Committee, adding to his existing responsibilities as the head of the senior selection committee. The senior selection committee includes Tauseef Ahmed, Wajahatullah Wasti, and Wasim Haider, while the junior selection committee consists of Aamer Nazir, Javed Hayat, Mahmood Hamid, Naveed Latif, Salman Ahmed, and Sanaullah Baloch. In a separate development, former captain Mohammad Hafeez recently announced his resignation from the PCB Technical Committee via a post on X (formerly known as Twitter), expressing his gratitude to chairman Zaka Ashraf and conveying his best wishes to Pakistan cricket. Hafeez's decision to step down from the committee came after a brief tenure of just under two months.

WHEN BATTLE IS SPIRITUAL When the battle is spiritual, it means you are fighting with forces you cannot see. You may hear a voice calling your name, but can't see anyone. It is a spiritual battle. When you are pressed down in your sleep or attacked in your dream, or you are always being pursued, or when you wake up, you see mysterious marks on your body, or you usually eat food or sexually harassed in the dream, these are spiritual battles. You can't confront these powers physically. When someone place a curse on you or cast a spell on you through divination or enchantment or by means of a charm, these are spiritual battles. PRESS RELEASE GLOBAL SECURITY: IGP URGES FAITHFUL TO BE LAW-ABIDING, EMBRACE PEACE Orders Adequate Deployment of Operatives for Security, Safety of All In light of the current global security challenges, with particular attention to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, the Inspector-General of Police, Acting IGP Kayode Adeolu Egbetokun, NPM, Ph.D., emphasizes the importance of law-abiding conduct and the pursuit of peace in all interactions with fellow members of the public. He urges individuals to refrain from making statements or engaging in actions that may disrupt the prevailing peace within our beloved nation. The IGP made this call while charging the mobile policemen, operatives of the Department of Force Intelligence, Zonal and State Departments of Intelligence, as well as officers and personnel stationed at various diplomatic missions and facilities. He emphasized the need for their preparedness in maintaining law and order, with a focus on safeguarding lives and property within the country. Furthermore, the IGP has tasked Commissioners of Police and their supervisory Assistant Inspectors-General of Police to maintain a heightened state of readiness among all personnel under their command. The Inspector-General of Police similarly encourages all citizens and residents of Nigeria to eschew sentimental sympathies that could potentially exacerbate tensions and disrupt the harmonious coexistence of our communities. He reaffirms the commitment of the Nigeria Police in swiftly addressing any activities that may encroach upon the fundamental rights of all individuals. ACP OLUMUYIWA ADEJOBI, mnipr, mipra, FORCE PUBLIC RELATIONS OFFICER, FORCE HEADQUARTERS, ABUJA 19TH OCTOBER, 2023.

Whether you realize it or not, you‚Äôre always in a growth process. This process is defined by the relationship between your self-awareness right now, and a new, more expanded version of yourself trying to emerge. Sometimes, the meeting of these two processes leads to an easy, liberating transformation; you sense a needed change and are able to do it. But more often, your current consciousness blocks the required change. This creates conflict, tension, and pain. If your mind can‚Äôt accept, is afraid of, isn‚Äôt ready yet, or is simply unaware of how you need to grow, it forces the basic emotion driving your growth to mutate. Instead of experiencing power or creativity or playfulness or whatever is trying to emerge into your consciousness, the raw emotion behind the new process manifests as a disturbance, a problem, a ‚Äúsymptom.‚Äù The fundamental emotion driving your issue is right, but it manifests in a negative way. Conventional mental health practice misses the mark by just trying to suppress your pain‚Äîthe disturbing manifestation of your process. Doing so, throws out the baby with the bathwater. Instead, you must learn how to reverse the mutation, uncover the hidden emotion driving your feelings, thoughts, and actions. This leads to liberation and expansion‚Äîthe true purpose of your problems. Just trying to get rid of your issue may reduce discomfort but it kills your growth. Your problem is your process! Behind your nasty inner critic, impossible relationship, depression, anxiety, attention deficit, delusions, mood swings, health issues, or boredom is an unseen emotion, a felt sense, a creative power, a new understanding and self-awareness pushing forth, trying with all its blind might to become a conscious awareness in your psyche. No matter how bad your problem is, don‚Äôt dismiss it as a meaningless error in your life, an ‚Äúillness,‚Äù a pathology to ‚Äúdiagnose‚Äù and ‚Äútreat"; always keep faith and belief in that fact that it has a meaningful message, and keep working to connect with its potent, hidden emotion. Marschlins Castle: A Timeless Tale of Majesty and Mystery In the heart of the Swiss Alps, where the mountains kiss the sky and history whispers through the ages, there stands a silent sentinel of the past, Marschlins Castle. Its imposing stone walls rise majestically, a testament to centuries gone by. This castle, nestled within the picturesque Swiss countryside, tells a tale of grandeur, intrigue, and the souls who once called it home. A Glimpse into History Marschlins Castle, also known as Schloss Marschlins, finds its roots in the medieval period. Built in the 13th century, the castle stands as a symbol of the past, a testament to the architecture and engineering prowess of its time. Perched on a steep hill, it boasts an unassailable position with panoramic views of the surrounding Rhine Valley and the Swiss Alps. Its remarkable location makes it a sight to behold and a true marvel of medieval engineering. One can only imagine the awe of the 13th-century peasants as they gazed upon this fortress, a place they would never enter but a sight that would be forever etched in their memories. Marschlins Castle was a stronghold of power, a refuge, and a symbol of the ruling family's authority. The Hohenems, a prominent noble family of the time, constructed the castle, marking the beginning of a legacy that would span centuries. Architectural Marvel The architectural magnificence of Marschlins Castle is a sight to behold. Its formidable stone walls are a testament to the craftsmanship and engineering skills of the medieval era. The castle features a central tower that soars into the sky, offering a commanding view of the valley below. Its crenellated parapets and imposing walls add to its medieval charm. Within its walls, the castle boasts a great hall, living quarters, and chapels, all reflecting the grandeur of a bygone age. The fortress was ingeniously designed to withstand the tests of time, with thick walls and a well-conceived layout that made it impervious to siege. As visitors explore its chambers, they can't help but be transported back in time, imagining the daily lives of those who lived and ruled here. Tales of Nobility Marschlins Castle was not just a structure of stone and mortar; it was the stage for many remarkable stories, often intertwined with the noble families who called it home. The Hohenems family, who held this fortress for generations, left their mark on the history of the region. They were known for their power, wealth, and contributions to art and culture. One notable member of the Hohenems family was Kaspar von Hohenems, who lived during the late 16th century. Kaspar was a visionary and an ardent patron of the arts. He transformed Marschlins Castle into a center of culture, inviting artists, scholars, and musicians to his court. His passion for art led to the creation of exquisite frescoes that still adorn the castle's walls today, a testament to the Renaissance's blossoming in this remote Swiss stronghold. In the centuries that followed, the castle witnessed a succession of lords and ladies, each leaving their unique mark on the structure and the region. Marschlins Castle was not merely a residence but a symbol of nobility, culture, and an everlasting legacy. Mysteries and Legends Every castle harbors secrets and stories, and Marschlins Castle is no exception. It is said that beneath its sturdy foundations lies a labyrinth of tunnels that once served as escape routes, providing safe passage to the river during times of conflict. These secret passages have stirred the imagination of countless generations, and their mysteries are yet to be fully uncovered. Local legends also shroud the castle in mystery. The most famous tale revolves around a ghostly apparition that is said to haunt the castle. The spirit of a lady in white has been reported by numerous visitors and locals. Some say she is the restless soul of a lady who met a tragic fate within these walls, while others claim she is a guardian spirit, watching over the castle through the ages. Regardless of the truth, the legend adds an air of intrigue to this already captivating castle. Moments in Time While the castle has seen countless days and nights pass, some moments have left a deeper imprint in history. During the Napoleonic era, the castle was occupied by French troops. Their presence marked a significant chapter in the history of Marschlins Castle and the region. The castle's halls must have echoed with the sounds of foreign soldiers, and its walls bore witness to the turbulence of the time. Yet, it wasn't just the foreign soldiers who left their mark. Local folklore tells tales of a heroic resistance by the Swiss, who fought valiantly to reclaim the castle from the French invaders. These stories serve as a reminder of the indomitable spirit of the Swiss people and their deep connection to their land and history. ODA 595, part of Task Force Dagger, entered Afghanistan in the aftermath of the 9/11 attacks with the mission to dismantle the Taliban. Beginning their journey on October 5, 2001, ODA 595 made their way to Uzbekistan and, on October 19, crossed into Afghanistan via an MH-47 Chinook helicopter. Here, they established contact with Gen. Abdul Rashid Dostum and his Uzbek militia. Adapting swiftly to their new environment, the team even learned to ride horses, a crucial skill. On November 10, ODA 595 and their militia allies achieved a monumental victory by liberating Mazar-e-Sharif from the Taliban. This pivotal success set the stage for subsequent Taliban surrenders across Afghanistan, marking a turning point in the conflict. The ODA 595 horse soldiers are depicted in the book/movie "12 Strong." #ODA595 #TaskForceDagger #Afghanistan #Taliban #WarOnTerror #HorseSoldiers

Nestled in the heart of the picturesque Aveyron region of southern France, the Chateau de Najac stands as a timeless testament to the grandeur of the medieval era. This magnificent fortress, perched atop a rugged hill, overlooks the enchanting village of Najac with an air of regal authority, casting a mesmerizing spell over all who lay eyes upon it.

Constructed in the 13th century during the tumultuous times of the Albigensian Crusade, the Chateau de Najac was not just a symbol of power but a guardian of a region rife with conflict. Its formidable stone walls, constructed to withstand sieges, rise majestically from the rocky terrain, each stone echoing centuries of history and power. 

As you approach the chateau, the very journey to its gates is an adventure through time, as you tread the very path that knights and noble ladies once walked, perhaps en route to or returning from the Crusade. 

Within the chateau's walls, the ambiance is nothing short of awe-inspiring. A tranquil courtyard, surrounded by well-preserved battlements, transports you back to the days when chivalry reigned supreme. The whispers of the wind and the echoing footsteps serve as a haunting reminder of all who have passed through these hallowed halls.

Stepping into the chateau's interiors, you are enveloped by a sense of mystery and antiquity. Stone archways lead you into dimly lit chambers where the tapestries tell stories of valor and love, offering a glimpse into the courtly life of the Middle Ages. The great hall, with its vaulted ceilings and colossal hearth, exudes an aura of grandeur that only the noblest of feasts and gatherings could have filled.

But it is from the highest tower of the Chateau de Najac that you are truly transported to another world. Ascend the winding staircase to be greeted by a panoramic vista that sweeps across the Aveyron landscape, just as it did when this fortress was both a stronghold and a refuge during its tumultuous history.

In every corner of the Chateau de Najac, you can almost hear the echoes of battles won and lost, and the whispers of lovers who once sought refuge in its walls. This medieval masterpiece is more than a monument; it is a living, breathing testament to human history, offering a profound connection to the past that is both emotive and stirring. A visit to the Chateau de Najac is a journey through time, an encounter with the spirits of chivalry, and an opportunity to lose oneself in the enchanting story of France's medieval heritage.

Canadian Inuit artist Kenojuak Ashevak, in Cape Dorset is considered the first Inuit woman to form part of the Cape Dorset recorders, draftsmen and designers cooperative, which receives support from the Canadian government. She was born in 1927 in an igloo at a nomadic Inuit camp on the south coast of Baffin Island. Her father was a hunter and well-respected shaman who was killed because of a conflict with Christian missionaries in 1933, when she was just 6. It was his mother who taught him during her childhood the traditional plastic arts of his people. During her life he worked different techniques of drawing, engraving and also addressed graphic design. In 1963, when Kenojuak was 35 years old, the National Film Board of Canada made a short documentary about her life, family and artistic work, titled ‚ÄúEskimo Artist: Kenojuak,‚Äù which was nominated for the Hollywood Oscars. In 2004 she became the first Inuit person to design a stained glass, located in the John Bell Chapel at Appleby College in Oakville, Ontario. The vast majority of her works are held at the National Gallery of Canada in Ottawa.

text: Tupua Tamasese Lealofi I, c.1902-05 Tupua Tamasese Lealofi and the scientist, Otto Tetens, who took this photograph, formed a close friendship after Mr Tetens arrived in Samoa in 1902 and set up the observatory at Mulinu‚Äôu, Apia (click image for full height). Tamasese lived nearby and Tetens often breakfasted with him. Lealofi, the son of Titimaea, was a handy tufuga fai fale and he and his daughters assisted the German scientist with fale construction, making and fitting roof thatching and blinds, pola, for some of the buildings that housed observatory equipment. Tetens diary recounts that Tamasese‚Äôs daughters sometimes came to get water from his tank using empty coconuts as containers. Though the family seat for Tamasese was at Vaimoso, he was apparently living at Mulinu‚Äôu at this time in an official residence following the resolution of the turbulent events of 1898-99. The death of paramount chief Malietoa Laupepa in 1898 had led to a power struggle among Tama-a-Aiga contenders for leadership, a contest that embroiled America, Germany and Britain in Samoan affairs, as all parties - local and international - tried to sort out a solution. The confused situation saw courtroom battles and armed conflict, and the eventual ascendancy of the popular Mata‚Äôafa Iosefo. At the height of this crisis Tupua Tamasese Lealofi had to seek safety on a British navy ship, where he spent several months under protection. The disturbances led directly to the German annexation of Samoa, after which Tamasese was paid an annuity and lived peaceably at Mulinu‚Äôu, in close political collaboration with Mata‚Äôafa Iosefo. Later he moved to Vaimoso where he died in 1915, apparently of pneumonia and a throat infection. VICE ADMIRAL GAVAN IS THE 30TH PCG COMMANDANT üáµüá≠ Department of Transportation (DOTr) Secretary Jaime Bautista announces the appointment of CG VICE ADMIRAL RONNIE GIL LATORILLA GAVAN as the 30th Philippine Coast Guard (PCG) Commandant during the Change of Command Ceremony at the National Headquarters, Port Area, Manila, today, 19 October 2023. In his speech, the Transportation Secretary expressed his trust and confidence that CG Vice Admiral Gavan would efficiently steer the PCG in implementing the "White Hull Approach" towards upholding maritime security and safety in the country's exclusive economic zones. "Admiral Art was hailed for his innate peace mindset that steered the country away from any deterioration in the volatile situation at the West Philippine Sea," DOTr Secretary Bautista said. "My belief that Vice Admiral Ronnie Gavan will do the same is anchored on his record of shifting to the 'White Hull Approach' when securing our maritime borders and his introduction of female radio operators, called 'Angels of the Sea,' as a way of diffusing tension during sea conflict," he furthered. Moreover, the Transportation Secretary emphasized President Ferdinand Marcos Jr's directives to the PCG during its 122nd founding anniversary as it moved forward to provide better public service to the Filipino nation. "I expect the PCG to provide steadfast service and dedication to duty during times of calamity; uphold our country's maritime security and promote our maritime rights; do its part in fighting smuggling; protect our marine environment; and secure the safety of our fishermen when pursuing their means of livelihood," DOTr Secretary Bautista highlighted. "The Department of Transportation firmly stands with you in your plans and efforts to improve, expand, and modernize your capabilities and services so you can level up your efforts at securing the welfare of our people and our nation," he concluded. President Ferdinand Bongbong Marcos Jr chose CG Vice Admiral Gavan among five recommended candidates to take over the Coast Guard helm following the retirement of CG Admiral Artemio Abu after over 35 years of public service on the same date. Before the said appointment, CG Vice Admiral Gavan served as the PCG's Deputy Commandant for Administration. He was also instrumental in training and capacity-building female Coast Guardians as radio operators dubbed "Angels of the Sea" on board PCG vessels patrolling the West Philippine Sea (WPS). The 30th PCG Commandant is a proud member of the Philippine Military Academy (PMA) Maalab Class of 1993. [File photos] #DOTrPH üáµüá≠ #CoastGuardPH #MaritimeSectorWorks

HOUSE SPEAKER ROMUALDEZ, MIGDAKE SAUP PINANSYAL KING PAMILYA CASTELVI‚ÄîTinagun ya king Barangay Juliana king syudad San Fernando y House Speaker Ferdinand Martin Romualdez niting October 18, 2023 ban personal a idake ing saup pinansyal (P500,000) para king pamilya ning meyangu a bie a Overseas Filipino Worker king Israel a y Paul Vincent Castelvi. Kayabe y Mayor Vilma Balle-Caluag, Pampanga Third District Representative Cong. Aurelio ‚ÄúDong‚Äù Gonzales, at y Governor Dennis ‚ÄúDelta‚Äù Pineda, agnan-agnan la reting tinagun king bale ning pamilya ng Castelvi ban idake mu rin ing pamakirame at saup kareng kapamilya ning OFW. Agpang kang Speaker Romualdez, dapot alang ulaga ning saup ing maka-aru king sakit a panamdaman da ring melakwan a pamilya, metung mu kanung paralan iti ban ipakit at ibie ning gubyernu ing pamangailangan da reti kabang balawus ing pamagobra ban asiguradu ing kaligtasan da ning balang Pilipinung apektadu king Israel-Hamas conflict. Pasasalamat ing dinake ng Mayor Caluag kang Speaker Romualdez kabang pengaku mu rin ing maging balawus a suporta ning lukal a kapanibalan ning syudad San Fernando para kareng pamilya nang Castelvi. Kayabe la namang tinagun di Pampanga Third District Board Member Alyssa Michaela ‚ÄúMica‚Äù Gonzales at City Councilor Brenz Gonzales. | CIO-PCM, RMM --- Bumisita sa Barangay Juliana sa syudad San Fernando si House Speaker Ferdinand Martin Romualdez nitong October 18, 2023, upang personal na iabot ang tulong pinansyal (P500,000) sa pamilya ng nasawing Overseas Filipino Worker sa Israel na si Paul Vincent Castelvi. Aurelio ‚ÄúDong‚Äù Gonzales, at Governor Dennis ‚ÄúDelta‚Äù Pineda, sabay-sabay ang mga ito na nagtungo sa bahay ng pamilya ni Castelvi upang ipaabot muli ang tulong at pakikiramay. Ayon kay Speaker Romualdez, walang halaga ng tulong ang tunay na makakapagbigay ng lunas sa sakit na nararamdaman ng naiwang pamilya ni Castelvi, ngunit ito ay isang paraan lamang upang maipakita ng gobyerno ang tulong sa pangangailangan nila, habang patuloy ang pagta-trabaho upang masiguro ang kaligtasan ng bawat Pilipinong apektado ng Israel-Hamas conflict. Pasasalamat ang ipinaabot ni Mayor Caluag kay Speaker Romualdez at ipinangako ang patuloy na suporta ng lokal na pamahalaan ng syudad San Fernando sa pamilya ni Castelvi. Kasama ring bumisita sa nasabing pamilya sina Pampanga Third District Board Member Alyssa Michaela ‚ÄúMica‚Äù Gonzales at City Councilor Brenz Gonzales. | CIO-PCM, RMM #FernandinoKaKayabeKa

#Leo: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê Leo is Thalapathy Vijay's career best as a performer. He NAILS it & I absolutely loved his range. Loki interviews la promise panna maari, "Idhu varikum paakadha oru Vijay anna va kaamika try panirken". On this promise, he certainly delivered. Trisha-Vijay emotional portions laam superb. Ani kills it as usual, especially in the first half. The 'I'm Scared' track is an absolute screamer & Leo OST in general is something you're definitely gonna see me use a lot in my stories. VFX is insane & the entire Hyena portion is so well done. A huge step up for Tamil Cinema in terms of filmmaking. Subramani is surely gonna win a lot of hearts. The filmmaking & camerawork is incredible. Andha 2nd half la Das n Co factory la vara 'oru moving camera' sequence absolutely blew my mind. The movie is a proper theatrical experience. Padathla enga prechni na, second half la vara villains character development dhaan. Harold Das & Antony Das characters innum better aa ezhudhirkalaam nu feel pannen. Loki sonna maari, "ennoda minimum guarantee second half, last 40 mins". Yes, last 40 mins were pure cinematic experience & seriyaana action extravaganza (Anbariv, take a bow), aana andha action conflict nadakarthukaana purpose fully convincing aa screen la reflect aagaliyo nu oru question. Can't wait for Baddy's post morten analysis with Loki now to listen to his explanation. Padam overall'aa enaku epdi nu keteenga na, I'd say Leo is not Loki's career best but still a very good movie I totally enjoyed & will surely watch again, with an OUTRAGEOUS first half (4.5/5:=:http://invalid.invalid/5) & a second half with some cluttered writing/character sketching of the bad guys, ending with a bang with a great climax sequence (3.5/5:=:http://invalid.invalid/5). The movie has a lot of surprises, W.O.W moments & is technically brilliant. Nichiyama indha padathuku noothuku ezhuvathi ettu markugal (78/100) kudupen, adhukaana ella thagudhi yum irukunga Leo kitta. Defenataa theatre la poi experience panna vendiya padam.

ùóßùóµùó≤ ùóßùóµùóøùó≤ùó≤ ùóú‚ÄôùòÄ ùòà ùòäùò©ùò≥ùò™ùò¥ùòµùò™ùò¢ùòØ‚Äôùò¥ ùòùùò™ùò¶ùò∏ ùò∞ùòØ ùòóùò∂ùò≥ùò¢ ùòìùò∂ùò¨ùò¢ ùòùùò¶ùò®ùò¢‚Äôùò¥ ùòàùò≥ùò≥ùò¶ùò¥ùòµ Growing up in an environment where every member of the family should actively participate in church activities, and also loving the art form of drag, Pura Luka Vega‚Äôs (often shortened as PLV, and uses they/them pronouns) arrest brought me to a realm of confusion, making me question myself how much of a Christian I am and how much I appreciate art. I‚Äôd like to walk you through that realm‚Ä¶ Mark 3:28-29 says, ‚ÄúAssuredly, I say to you, all sins will be forgiven the sons of men, and whatever blasphemies they may utter; but he who blasphemes against the Holy Spirit never has forgiveness, but is subject to eternal condemnation." Digging the dictionary, blasphemy means great disrespect shown to God, or to something holy, or to something said or done that shows this kind of disrespect. From this, they did commit a blasphemous act, did they not? They sure will be subjected to eternal damnation, correct? Alright, let‚Äôs move forward. Drag is exaggeratedly dressing and acting as the gender that drag artists identify with or with whom they associate themselves. This is typically done for entertainment purposes such as comedy, impersonation, dancing, singing, acting, lip-syncing, or any combination of the aforementioned. In explicit terms, drag is an art‚Äî and art is free expression. So they did art, didn‚Äôt they? It was their form of expression, right? So Pura Luka Vega did both‚Äîthey blasphemed by expressing their art through drag. Then what? Let‚Äôs walk further. Here is where the most disturbing part of this aghast place, I call it the 3Is‚ÄîIronies, Inconsistencies, and I-pocrisies. First, the Ironies: the third chapter of the book of Mark talks about a conflict over healing on the Sabbath, the commissioning of the 12 Apostles, a conflict with the Jerusalem scribes, and a meeting of Jesus with his own family. Any person exposed to church activities, seminars, and workshops knows that it is unfair to use a verse or two from the Bible without purely understanding the context. Before Jesus spoke to them in parables, teachers of the law called Jesus being possessed by demons and that He was a charlatan Himself. Then He spoke those words in Mark 3:28-29, yet people who rally against PLV weaponize these verses, condemning them for their act. Yet, scrutinizing it with meticulous attention, He said that anyone who blasphemes shall be forgiven, however, anyone who blasphemes the Holy Spirit will never be forgiven. As Christians, we are a monotheistic religion; we believe in One God in Three Persons: the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit, or basically, ‚ÄúThe Holy Trinity‚Äù. However, it raises the question of why the Holy Spirit, uniquely, is singled out as the entity that shall not be blasphemed. Why is the Holy Spirit the sole exception to this rule of forgiveness? Let‚Äôs flip a few pages back in Mark 1:4. Mark makes it clear that sins are forgiven only if a person repents. This means that in verse 28 of Mark 3, it says that all sins and blasphemies will be forgiven if the person truly repents‚Äîwherein the unique and decisive role of the Holy Spirit plays a part in our salvation. When we turn away from the glory of God the Father and God the Son and embrace sin, it is therefore bad. But blasphemy against the Holy Spirit puts us beyond repentance, for it rejects the means through which an individual can seek forgiveness and turn to God. And blasphemy of the Holy Spirit is not calling Jesus names or harboring negative thoughts about Him; it is asserting that Jesus' ministry is that of the devil because he is supported by an evil spirit. As PLV‚Äôs performance only featured God the Son, are they really going to be damned forever? Did they really commit the unforgivable sin? Moving on to the next I: Inconsistencies. After being declared persona non grata from several parts of the country, PLV was arrested on October 4 for violating Article 2 of the Revised Penal Code (RPC) for spreading ‚Äúimmoral doctrines, obscene publications and exhibitions, and indecent shows,‚Äù with the court setting a bail of P72,000.00. What makes this inconsistent is the vagueness of their violation and the RPC itself. It was enacted in the early 1930s, which is almost a century old upon the arrest of PLV. Plus, what is more inconsistent is that Article II, Section 6 of the 1987 Constitution states that the separation of the Church and the State shall be inviolable, yet the backbone of PLV‚Äôs arrest was strongly based on Christians feeling angry about their performance. Pass√© laws and mentalities truly impede the development of a nation. It hinders us from reaching our full potential‚Äîto be at par with high-statured countries. Moving forward, Pura Luka Vega is expressing their art through this performance. Let‚Äôs talk about the setting‚Äîwere they in a church? Are they being watched by children? Is there such a thing as an invalid form of art? I guess (truncated)

Chevening/Commonwealth Scholarship Essay Questions and How to Answer them: Q1. How your proposed study relates to: (a) development issues at the global, national and local level? (b) development issues connected to your chosen CSC theme and the wider sector? This is how I answered mine: I chose MSc International Conflict and Cooperation (course) I told them I wanted to work on the Boko Haram issue (problem) I chose "strengthening global peace, security and governance" (a CSC theme much related to peace and conflict). Martin's comments: How to fail this essay: Write about everything that comes to your mind but ignore the word "RELATE" A good way to fail this essay is to choose a course titled "MSc Entrepreneurship" and to talk about a global issue of terrorism while choosing a CSC theme on Health. A good way to score points in this essay: Draw a connection across your course of study, the issue you want to solve (terrorism, hunger etc) and the CSC theme you have chosen. The key word here is "RELATE". Eyes on the ball. Let your course, problem and CSC theme be related. Any "cut and join" tendency here, you are gone. Question 2 dropping soon with answers.

In part of our Unshaken Faith podcast episode yesterday ("How to Pray During War"), Alisa and I shared the prayer requests of a Christian mom who contacted me from Jerusalem. Several people have asked for her words to be given here in written form in order to pray with her more readily and share her requests with others. Here are the beautiful words she offered. *** Firstly, the Messianic community is praying for the salvation of Israel. We are praying that they would see the Lord is faithful and come to saving knowledge of their own Messiah. We are also praying for the salvation of our Arab neighbors. For brotherly love, and for them to have the Lord's heart for Israel, as the apple of His eye. We are praying for the IDF to safely and effectively dismantle Hamas for the good of the entire region. So much of our prayer meetings are focused on praying for the IDF, for their safety, and wisdom. For miraculous protection and discernment. We are also in prayer for soldiers in the units cleaning the villages that were massacred and they have asked for prayer for their units, as they are seeing hard and painful things. We are praying for the hostages to remain safe and to be returned to their families quickly. The Northern border is a huge concern. Hamas, Hezbollah, and the Palestinian Islamic Jihad are all Iranian proxies. They all work with Iran to accomplish their evil agenda and we are praying for protection on the Northern border where the cells have more direct access to Iranian support. We are also asking the Lord to give us time to grieve, as a nation, and for the families who lost loved ones in the massacre. We went from devastation and shock to defending our nation, without properly sitting Shivah (the 7 day mourning tradition of the Jewish people). We're also all very tired. Please pray for the civilians to be able to rest and sleep well. We're all working really hard in a variety of volunteer capacities and the adrenaline let downs from the sirens are exhausting. We are a nation of overwhelmed people right now and we need to rest. Hope. Please pray for hope and that the Israeli people will see the Lord and be aware of his comfort after this loss. The propaganda war is very stressful for us as well. The left/woke ideology hates everything God loves, including Israel. It's really hard to see truth twisted, and Israel presented as an oppressor. We are constantly praying for the nations to know what is Truth, what is true, and what is factual. Our army is the most heavily scrutinized in the world and we go beyond what is required to ensure ethical processes. We are dealing with people who make that very difficult. Endurance. We don't know how long this mission will take and we need to endure in the Lord, in healthy and holy ways. Wisdom about decisions big and small, whether its when and where to go to the grocery store, or if/when to evacuate. (So far our entire community of friends is still here. No one has left). Pray for the moms who are now single parenting after the husbands left for reserves. Pray for them to get the rest and help they need from the community. Please pray for the children to be shielded from trauma, both in lived experiences and images in the media. Many of our friends who were here for the Gulf war as children said it increased their faith, so there are ways this can be a positive as long as we keep their needs at the forefront. *** Thank you all for praying alongside this mom and so many like her who are in the middle of the conflict. If you'd like to leave her a word of encouragement, please do so in the comments and I will share with her.

CRIME ALERTüö®üö®üö® Williamsburg robbery/murder: Family of businessman shattered by his death The family of 59-year-old Akbhar Sain, who was murdered on Wednesday morning during a robbery, is still trying to come to grips with his death. The man who operated the Akbhar Sain Supermarket at the lower flat of his Williamsburg, Corentyne Berbice home, was beaten to death at around 2:00 hours by Satesh Ramneries. The suspect, who confessed, said after he broke into the establishment, a scuffle ensued between Akbhar and him, during which he hit the man with a piece of wood to his head. After the lashes, Akbhar collapsed and died. Neighbors who heard the incident contacted the police, and they rushed to the scene. Police said the suspect was seen hiding behind a washing machine in the back verandah in the upper flat of the businessman's two-storey house. The police challenged him, and he received a shot in the right arm. A search was conducted on his person, and a quantity of Guyana currency was found stashed in his crotch. The suspect was escorted to the Port Mourant Public Hospital, where he was seen by a doctor on duty. At the time of the incident, Akbhar was living alone. His gun was found at the scene. The suspect remains in custody as police continue their investigation. Meanwhile, the now-dead man's cousin, Zamin Djamier told the Guyana Daily News that Akbhar operated the supermarket for decades. "He was a very hardworking person; a man who never rest. He was all for his family and a very decent person. He have never been in conflict with anybody, " he said. Djamier continued, "It pains me to know that an individual who had given his all, would have been having his demise in this way. The entire family is being shattered. I spoke with his brother who lives in New York and his next brother who lives in Canada and nobody can come to grips with what has happened here this morning. We are all shattered."

text: Unearthed in Germany, DNA extracted from bones and teeth within a 4,600-year-old Stone Age burial site has yielded the earliest proof of the nuclear family system as a societal structure. Within this discovery, a poignant narrative unfolds: Two parents and their two sons, laid to rest together, their lives cut short by a tragic conflict over highly coveted fertile farmland in Europe. These collective burials, seemingly interwoven, provide a window into the past, revealing a tale of violent endings. The individuals belonged to the Corded Ware culture, named after their distinctive pottery decoration technique involving twisted cord patterns.

ArchAngel Michael's Discourse~ ( Ronna Herman Vezane) ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è We will now help you build your Pyramid of Power, where you will go in your quiet time and sleep time to receive healing, nurturance ‚Äî to create that which you desire, and to also seek a Divine Solution for any situation or challenge that you may face. In whatever way you perceive, envision a Pyramid of Light. Through your intent, state that this pyramid is manifested in the fifth dimension. There is a capstone on your pyramid and it contains a spiraling Rainbow Ray of Light, which contains all the colors, virtues, and attributes of our Father/Mother God. As you move into the interior of your pyramid, look around: the walls and floor radiate an inner Light, and there are twelve crystal chairs in a circle. (You may wish to add more from time to time.) There is a Crystal Table in the center, and when you lie on it, it conforms perfectly to your body. There is a magnificent clear quartz crystal hanging over the center of the table. The crystal is faceted at both ends and the upper portion penetrates the capstone of the pyramid. This is the basic structure of your pyramid. However, we suggest that you add your own personal touches as you visit your Sacred Temple, and make it your own. We will give you several examples of how you may most effectively use your pyramid. Healing Conflict with Another Let us say that you have a situation of conflict with someone in your life. text: PRESS RELEASE BANJUL ‚Äì 19th October, 2023 - The Government of the Republic of The Gambia joins the International Community including United Nations (UN), Organization of Islamic Cooperation (OIC), The African Union (AU) and others in vehemently condemning the Israeli Military operations in Gaza for almost two weeks including stoppage of electricity, water, food aid, medical supplies, fuel and the indiscriminate bombing of Al-Ahli Baptist Hospital in Gaza where over 500 innocent Palestinians were killed mostly women, children, the disabled and sick patients. Taking into cognizance the fact that Palestinians have for long been fighting for their legitimate and inalienable rights for self-determination for over 75 years without any success; and given the usurpation of their territories and freedoms by the Occupying Power, the State of Israel, their situation became so dire that utter desperation resulted in this unfortunate war in Gaza. The Government of The Gambia calls for an unconditional ceasefire and the release of all hostages to prevent more bloodshed and the proposed invasion of Gaza which could result not only in more deaths and destruction but also in forcibly displacing Palestinian citizens in Gaza and the West Bank and in doing so build more Israeli settlements in those areas. The Government of the Gambia further appeals to the International Community to compel the Occupying Power to abide by the tenets of the Peace process, International Law, International Humanitarian Law and UN Security Council Resolutions. Failure to do so is bound to prolong the conflict, cause further instability and diminish the chances fora resolution of this conflict. The Government of The Gambia, given that Israeli Military aggression is used as an instrument of collective punishment causing huge loss of life, property and injuries on both sides since the occupation of Palestine in 1948, calls for an International Peace Conference for a permanent and durable solution to this very protracted Palestinian problem. The Government of The Gambia considers that: the best option for a peaceful settlement of this dispute between the two parties is not a military one but a comprehensive Peace Accord based on the "Two-Party Solution" guaranteeing both States their legitimate and inalienable rights to full sovereignty and self-determination. The Government of The Gambia, in this context, reaffirms its support for the Palestinian people to regain their legitimate national rights, as recognized by the International Community through its recognition of a State of Palestine within the borders of June 4th, 1967, with Al-Quds Al- Shareef as its Capital as indicated in all relevant UN, OIC and AU Resolutions. On behalf of H.E. The President of the Republic of The Gambia Mr. Adama Barrow, The Government and People of The Gambia express deepest condolences for the tragic loss of life and property on both sides and wish all those injured speedy recovery and pray that this tragedy which continues to unfold before our own eyes will soon cease and never be repeated again.

EXAMPLES OF HOW TO COMMUNICATE WITH AN ALIENATED CHILD Staying assertive and setting boundaries Firstly, remember to pick your battles and "strike when the iron is cold." There is no point trying to converse with a heated angry child or teen. Find a time when they are hopefully calmer and preferably not in earshot of the alienating parent. Here are some examples you can play around with... üåªWhen it comes to defining expectations: "We can have a productive conversation when we both speak respectfully. If you raise your voice or make hurtful comments, I will disengage from the conversation until we can talk calmly." üåªWhen entitlement issues are a concern: "I hope that when we spend time together, we can share our thoughts respectfully and consider each other's feelings. Our interactions need to be a positive experience for both of us." üåªPutting a limit on finance entitlement: "I genuinely want to help with your needs to the best of my ability, but it's important that we discuss and agree on what's reasonable and practical within my financial budget." üåªWhen privacy is an issue: "I highly value my privacy. Please respect my personal space and belongings as you would want yours to be respected. üåªWhen you need to promote more respectful communication: "Having good conversation happens when we're both kind and respectful in our words. If things start to feel too intense or if someone says something unkind, it would be a good idea for us to pause the conversation and chat again when we're both feeling calmer." üåªWhen time spent with you is an issue: "We've talked about the special times we've set aside to be together, which means a lot to me. It can be disappointing when you don't join me at the agreed times, especially when I have planned..." HAVING DIFFICULTIES WITH YOUR CHILD SPENDING TIME WITH YOU OR YOUR FAMILY: * Let them know you understand that they might have mixed feelings about family time. * Talk about all the fun and happy moments you've had together as a family, like holidays, birthdays or when you laughed a lot. * Explain that families are like a team. They help each other in good times and when things get tough. Being together helps you all stay strong. * Families give each other love and care. When you spend time together, it makes your love even stronger and helps you understand each other better. * Always remind them that you love them very much. Being with them helps you both feel even closer to each other. * Let them know it's okay to share their thoughts and feeling and that you will always be there to listen. * Talk about all the exciting things you'll do together as a family in the future. It's something to be excited about! * Explain everything in a way they can easily understand, using simple words and examples they can relate to. * Remember, it might take some time for them to fully understand why family time is important. Be patient and keep being kind and supportive. * By being a part of family activities and showing that you enjoy spending time together, you're teaching them how important family is. #communication #alienatedchild #conflict #boundaries Photo credit: Orlando Allo on Unsplash
