Giuseppe Cicozzetti foto Bert Hardy BERT HARDY London, May 13, 1940. The United Kingdom is at war with Nazi Germany. In a speech to the House of Commons, Prime Minister Winston Churchill announces that the country will find itself in the midst of a great ordeal that can only be left with "blood, sweat and tears". The bombings that followed devastated London but did not bend it. The ordeal, with attached horrors, is told by a self-taught photographer, a documentary filmmaker who has been able to accredit him and who has taken to following the troop movements in war, starting from the Allied landing in Normandy. His name is Bert Hardy (1913-1995). In the photographs I propose to your attention, Hardy recounts the post-war phase of a proud and full of hopeful country that comes from having emerged victorious from a conflict that has set Europe on fire, but whose signs of horror are etched in everyone's moral like an indelible scratch. Except for the first photograph, which refers to the period of the living war threat - we see in fact a large number of children about to leave London to be saved in the Counties outside London, as a guarantee of a future - all the others belong to the period of reconstruction, in a time span ranging from '48 to the end of the 50s. London wants to forget and starting over. It will not be easy and in every shot of Bert Hardy we catch the confused atmosphere of those years, to which a thick layer of fog contributes to make an even more nuanced horizon. From there, in a few years everything will change, a wave of novelty will force every Brit, especially the young, to look to the future with greater confidence. They will be the years of the Beatles and of the "Swinging London‚Äù. And we know how it went. But the London of Bert Hardy, "that" London, has an absolute testimonial value. His photographs, all taken rigorously with his loyal Leica, are more effective than an essay and from whose reading we derive a dramatic and beautiful fresco. Whether it's children playing, neighbors chatting, reading women or prostitutes gravitating around Piccadilly Circus, you can breathe such an air of great social restitution. Inzamam-ul-Haq, the former Pakistan cricket captain, is reportedly considering stepping down from his role as chief selector due to disagreements with the Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB). Sources suggest that Inzamam is dissatisfied with the appointment of Shahid Anwar as the head coach of the U19 men's team, as he had advocated for former Pakistan cricketer Mohammad Yousaf to be given the position. This is not the first instance of conflict between Inzamam and the PCB, as they have had differences in the past as well. Recently, Inzamam had signed a contract worth Rs2.5 million per month with the PCB. However, the PCB has refuted these claims, with a spokesperson stating that Inzamam had actively participated in the selection process for the U19 men's team and the women's A team, and they had no knowledge of any discord between Inzamam and the board. Earlier in the month, Inzamam was appointed as the chairman of the Junior Men's Cricket Selection Committee, adding to his existing responsibilities as the head of the senior selection committee. The senior selection committee includes Tauseef Ahmed, Wajahatullah Wasti, and Wasim Haider, while the junior selection committee consists of Aamer Nazir, Javed Hayat, Mahmood Hamid, Naveed Latif, Salman Ahmed, and Sanaullah Baloch. In a separate development, former captain Mohammad Hafeez recently announced his resignation from the PCB Technical Committee via a post on X (formerly known as Twitter), expressing his gratitude to chairman Zaka Ashraf and conveying his best wishes to Pakistan cricket. Hafeez's decision to step down from the committee came after a brief tenure of just under two months.

The news created shockwaves around the world. Those evil, genocidal Israelis bombed a hospital in Gaza, resulting in hundreds of deaths. Yet these monstrous Israelis targeted it for destruction, causing outrage and cries for vengeance around the globe, especially in the Muslim world. Of course, that‚Äôs not what happened. First, Israel doesn‚Äôt do that. Israel does not target hospitals and schools. Israel does not single out and destroy innocent non-combatants, especially women and children and the sick and elderly. And especially, at a time like this, Israel would not possibly do something like this. The backlash would be massive, and rightly so. In stark contrast, Hamas does do these very things. Hamas takes delight in slaughtering the innocent in the most grotesque, barbaric ways imaginable, filming it for the world to see. Israel does not. So, at the very worst, this would have been an errant strike by an Israeli pilot, a tragic event that would cause grief and pain in Israel as well, not dancing and celebrating in the streets. Saya telah menyampaikan Kenyataan Malaysia dalam Mesyuarat Luar Biasa Tergempar Jawatankuasa Eksekutif Pertubuhan Kerjasama Islam (OIC) Peringkat Menteri-Menteri Luar Negeri berkenaan serangan ketenteraan rejim Israel yang berterusan ke atas rakyat Palestin. Dalam Kenyataan ini, saya telah menggesa konflik Palestin-Israel dihentikan dengan kadar segera dan mendesak untuk menghentikan politics of dispossession, iaitu menyahkan hak dan tanah rakyat Palestin. Negara Anggota OIC, masyarakat antarabangsa dan negara-negara yang berpengaruh perlu mencari solusi ke arah ini. Saya juga telah menggesa masyarakat antarabangsa untuk menyokong pembukaan laluan kemanusiaan (humanitarian corridor) untuk menyampaikan bantuan kemanusiaan kepada rakyat Palestin. Mesyuarat ini telah menerima pakai satu dokumen hasil yang mengutuk sekeraskerasnya pencerobohan Israel terhadap Palestin. Dokumen ini juga menggesa agar pencerobohan Israel dihentikan serta-merta; pengepungan yang dikenakan ke atas Semenanjung Gaza oleh Israel ditamatkan; dan menyeru negara-negara dan masyarakat antarabangsa untuk menghulurkan bantuan kemanusiaan segera kepada rakyat Palestin. Malaysia turut mengecam secara serius insiden pengeboman Hospital Al-Ahli Al-Arabi di Utara Gaza, sehingga menyebabkan banyak kematian termasuk wanita dan kanak-kanak serta orang awam yang tidak bersalah. Perbuatan kejam ini jelas sekali bertentangan dengan nilai kemanusiaan dan melanggar undang-undang antarabangsa. Sebagai salah sebuah negara pengasas OIC, Malaysia terus komited dalam memperjuangkan hak-hak rakyat Palestin. Malaysia bersedia untuk bekerjasama dalam mana-mana usaha antarabangsa bagi mengumpul dan menghulurkan bantuan kemanusiaan secepat mungkin kepada rakyat Palestin. Malaysia juga sedang giat mengadakan perbincangan dengan pemimpin-pemimpin dunia bagi mencari kaedah terbaik untuk menghentikan konflik yang berlaku dan mencari penyelesaian masa kini dan masa hadapan rakyat Palestin agar lebih aman dan selamat. ------------------ I delivered Malaysia‚Äôs statement at the Extraordinary Emergency Meeting of the OIC Executive Committee at the level of Foreign Ministers to discuss the ongoing Israeli military aggression against the Palestinian people. In my statement, I stressed the need for the Israeli regime to cease the ongoing politics of dispossession, that is denying the rights and land of the Palestinian people. OIC Member States, the international community, especially States with influence need to find a solution in this direction. I also urge the international community to support the opening of humanitarian corridors to ensure the unhindered flow of aid to the Palestinian people. The meeting also adopted a Final Communique, strongly condemning the unprecedented Israeli aggression against civilians. The Final Communique also stressed, among others, the immediate cessation of the Israeli aggression against the people of Palestine; the immediate lifting of the siege imposed on the Gaza Strip; and called upon countries and the international community to extend the immediate provision of humanitarian aid to the Palestinian people. In the latest incident, Malaysia also seriously condemned the bombing of the Al-Ahli al-Arab Hospital in Northern Gaza, causing many deaths including women and children as well as innocent civilians. This brutal act is clearly against human values and does not comply with international law. As one of the founding members of the OIC, Malaysia remains committed to the Palestinian cause. Malaysia is prepared to participate in any international efforts to provide humanitarian aid and relief supplies to the Palestinians. Malaysia is also actively holding discussions with world leaders to find the best way to stop the ongoing conflict and to find a present solution for the sake of a more peaceful and secure future for the Palestinian people. #wismaputra #doczam #MalaysiaMadani #oicmeetingforpalestinians

IN PHOTOS | Pagdiriwang ng Katutubong Pamayanan Higaonon ICCs/IPs - Practitioners of Traditional Conflict Resolution The word Higaonon came from the words higad, meaning ‚Äòcoastal areas,‚Äô gaon, meaning ‚Äòmountains,‚Äô and onon, referring to the ‚Äòpeople.‚Äô They were originally called by outsiders as Higadnon, which means ‚Äòseaside dwellers.‚Äô Over time they were then called Higaonon when they were forced to move uplands as they chose peace over conflict when the settlers and the colonizers arrived during the Spanish period. By continuing to practice husay or traditional conflict resolution, the Higaonon managed to sustain peace within their community. The Higaonon of Caraga are descendants of Apo Nangadinag, one of the descendants of Apo Pabuloson, who is one of the main ancestors of the Higaonon of Northern Mindanao. Apo Nangadinag is an Alagaan priestess who wanted to achieve salvation as promised by the spiritual bird Andadapal found in Sinakungan, the mountain believed by all Higaonon as holy, where they celebrate the Dumalongdong. The ancestral domain of the Higaonon in Caraga Region is located in the forested interior planes and mountainous areas of Esperanza, Agusan del Sur and in the municipalities of Las Nieves, Buenavista, Nasipit and Carmen, in the Province of Agusan del Norte. The Higaonon can also be found in three provinces in Northern Mindanao, specifically in Bukidnon, Lanao del Norte, and Misamis Oriental. #BuwanNgKatutubo #protectipra #BagongPilipinas @followers Friends

BASAHIN I Cluster members nang Sectoral Unification, Capacity Building, Empowerment and Mobilization (SUCBEM), RTF-ELCAC ng Region IV-A nagpulong sa pangunguna ni Atty Roy Buenafe, Regional Director DOLE IV-A at Chairperson ng SUCBEM Cluster Region IV-A. Ang nasabing pulong ay dinaluhan nang ibat-ibang kinatawan nang ahensiya nang gobyerno na nakakasakop nang CALABARZON, kasama ang 2nd Civil-Military Operations Battalion, CMOR, PA na pinamunuan ni LTC FERDINAND BRUCE M TOKONG, 2CMOBn Commanding Officer noong ika-18 ng Oktubre taong kasalukuyan sa Juliet Hall, Hotel Marciano, Real, Calamba City, Laguna. Ang nasabing pulong ay naka sentro sa usaping pagpapalakas at pagpapaigting nang ugnayan nang ibat-ibang sangay nang pamahalaan upang matulungan at maipamahagi ang proyekto sa lahat ng apektadong sektor sa lipunan lalo na sa banta nang pandemya at terorismo. Napag-usapan din sa nasabing pulong ang mga programa at ibat-ibang assistance na naipamahagi at naipamigay na mula sa mga ahensiya nang pamahalaan mula sa BFAR, DA, DSWD, DILG, NCIP, PIA, DOLE at nang Philippine Army, AFP. Kasunod nito, pinag-usapan din sa nasabing pulong ang mga programa nang DOLE IV-A ang Kabuhayan Program sa pamamagitan ng DOLE Integrated Livelihood Program (DILP) na may tatlong bahagi ang; Kabuhayan Formation, Kabuhayan Enhancement at Kabuhayan Restoration at ibang programa tulad nang TUPAD- Tulong panghanapbuhay sa ating Disadvantage Workers Program. Sa mensahe ni Atty Roy Buenafe, aniya ang programa nang NTF ELCAC sa pamamagitan nang SUCBEM ay dapat nakatu-on duon sa pinaka-mahina na sektor nang lipunan upang maibigay ang tamang solusyun sa problema, tamang programa nang gobyerno para magkaroon sila nang tamang kapasidad para sa ika-uunlad nang kanilang buhay at makapamuhay nang mas mapayapa at tutulong para sa ika-uunlad nang bayan. Nagbigay din ng mensahe si LTC TOKONG at ibinahagi niya na dapat mas paigtingin pa ang pakikipag-ugnayan nang bawat ahensiya nang gobyerno sa pag bigay nang tulong at proteksiyon sa mga apektadong sektor nang lipunan lalo na ang sektor nang paggawa, kabataan at estudyante, kababaihan at magsasaka na naging pangunahing target nang panlilinlang at recruitment nang teroristang CPP/NPA/NDF upang maging parte sa pagsusulong nang teroristang armadong pakikibaka para pabagsakin ang ating gobyerno. Matatandaan natin na ang layunin nang Executive Order 70 sa pangunguna nang NTF ELCAC ay to End Local Communist Armed Conflict sa pamamagitan nang Whole of Nation Approach. Sinabi din nang ating PRESIDENT FERDINAND R MARCOS JR sa kanyang talumpati sa Davao noong October 2022 na (quote) "We will need to sustain it with the whole-of-nation approach to peace and development to prevent terrorist and lawless elements from recruiting, regrouping, and regaining power over our countrymen." (unquote). #2CMOBn #TFUgnay #StrongerArmyStrongerCountry #ATR2040 #PhilippineArmy

Tupua Tamasese Lealofi I, c.1902-05

Tupua Tamasese Lealofi and the scientist, Otto Tetens, who took this photograph, formed a close friendship after Mr Tetens arrived in Samoa in 1902 and set up the observatory at Mulinu‚Äôu, Apia (click image for full height).

Tamasese lived nearby and Tetens often breakfasted with him. Lealofi, the son of Titimaea, was a handy tufuga fai fale and he and his daughters assisted the German scientist with fale construction, making and fitting roof thatching and blinds, pola, for some of the buildings that housed observatory equipment. Tetens diary recounts that Tamasese‚Äôs daughters sometimes came to get water from his tank using empty coconuts as containers.

Though the family seat for Tamasese was at Vaimoso, he was apparently living at Mulinu‚Äôu at this time in an official residence following the resolution of the turbulent events of 1898-99. The death of paramount chief Malietoa Laupepa in 1898 had led to a power struggle among Tama-a-Aiga contenders for leadership, a contest that embroiled America, Germany and Britain in Samoan affairs, as all parties - local and international - tried to sort out a solution. The confused situation saw courtroom battles and armed conflict, and the eventual ascendancy of the popular Mata‚Äôafa Iosefo. At the height of this crisis Tupua Tamasese Lealofi had to seek safety on a British navy ship, where he spent several months under protection.

The disturbances led directly to the German annexation of Samoa, after which Tamasese was paid an annuity and lived peaceably at Mulinu‚Äôu, in close political collaboration with Mata‚Äôafa Iosefo. Later he moved to Vaimoso where he died in 1915, apparently of pneumonia and a throat infection.

Julia Margaret Cameron (British photographer) 1815 - 1879 Hypathia, 1868 albumen print, on a gilt-ruled mount 32 x 24.8 cm. (12.63 x 9.75 in.) signed, titled, and annotated 'From Life' and ‚ÄòMarie Spartali‚Äô by the photographer and with the Colnaghi blindstamp on the mount (Cox 469) private collection ¬© photo Sotheby's Hypatia was an Alexandrine Neoplatonist philosopher in Egypt who was the first well-documented woman in mathematics. As head of the Platonist school at Alexandria, she also taught philosophy and astronomy. As a Neoplatonist philosopher, she belonged to the mathematic tradition of the Academy of Athens, as represented by Eudoxus of Cnidus; she was of the intellectual school of the 3rd century thinker Plotinus, which encouraged logic and mathematical study in place of empirical enquiry and strongly encouraged law in place of nature. According to the only contemporary source, Hypatia was murdered by a Christian mob after being accused of exacerbating a conflict between two prominent figures in Alexandria: the governor Orestes and the Bishop of Alexandria. Kathleen Wider proposes that the murder of Hypatia marked the end of Classical antiquity, and Stephen Greenblatt observes that her murder "effectively marked the downfall of Alexandrian intellectual life". On the other hand, Maria Dzielska and Christian Wildberg note that Hellenistic philosophy continued to flourish in the 5th and 6th centuries, and perhaps until the age of Justinian. Source: Wikipedia * * * After receiving a camera as a gift, Julia Margaret Cameron began her career in photography at the age of forty-eight. She produced the majority of her work from her home at Freshwater on the Isle of Wight. By the coercive force of her eccentric personality, she enlisted everyone around her as models, from family members to domestic servants and local residents. The wife of a retired jurist, Cameron moved in the highest circles of society in Victorian England. She photographed the intellectuals and leaders within her circle of family and friends, among them the portrait painter George Frederick Watts, the astronomer Sir John Herschel, and the Poet Laureate Alfred, Lord Tennyson. She derived much of her subject inspiration from literature, and her work in turn influenced writers. In addition to literature, she drew her subject matter from the paintings of Raphael, Giotto, and Michelangelo, whose works she knew through prints that circulated widely in late nineteenth-century England. Summing up her influences, Cameron stated her photographic mission thus: "My aspirations are to ennoble Photography and to secure for it the character and uses of High Art by combining the real and Ideal and sacrificing nothing of the Truth by all possible devotion to Poetry and beauty." Source: J. Paul Getty Museum

‚ù§ On this day - 4th October 1841 ‚ù§
.
‚ù§ Birth of Maria Sophie Amalie - Naples Warrior Queen  ‚ù§

.
‚ù§ Born on 4th October 1841 to Duke Maximilian of Bavaria and Princess Ludovika, Maria Sophie Amalie had a privileged but turbulent childhood.
While she was born in the lap of luxury, her upbringing was very extraordinary due to her father‚Äôs eccentric ways.
The Duke encouraged his family to take up habits like horse riding, instead of reading and studying.
Needless to say, he imparted his sense of adventure onto his children, especially Maria Sophie.

‚ù§ At just 16 years of age, Maria was betrothed to Francis II, the Crown Prince of Naples.
Unfortunately, Maria still hadn‚Äôt gotten her period.
Since marriages were about siring royal heirs as quickly as possible, this posed a very big problem for Maria.

‚ù§ To try and remedy the situation, poor Maria was subjected to a brutal medical regime aimed at jumpstarting her period cycle.
From scorching hot baths to leeching, the young girl underwent various procedures.

‚ù§ Maria and Francis were a match made in hell, because they were polar opposites in personality and temperament.
While Francis was serious and devout, Maria was young, playful, and adventurous, which didn‚Äôt translate well into their bedroom activities.
As the tale goes, their wedding night comprised of Francis desperately praying, while Maria wept.

‚ù§ As it turns out, Maria wasn‚Äôt the only one with troubling medical conditions.
Francis was also hiding a shameful secret from everyone.
The prince suffered from a condition called Phimosis, which made intercourse incredibly painful.
This wholly blindsided young Maria, and their marriage suffered greatly as a result.

‚ù§ The marriage went from bad to worse with Francis‚Äô  ailment, and their incompatibility.
The prince naturally failed to meet his young wife‚Äôs appetites.
In fact, their marriage wasn‚Äôt consummated until years later, due to Francis‚Äô condition.

‚ù§ Barely a year after her nuptials, Prince Francis‚Äô father passed away, making him the King of Two Sicilies.
Overnight, Maria became a literal Queen.
While her queendom wasn‚Äôt as luxurious as one would hope, it allowed Maria to prove herself to the people of Europe and beyond.

‚ù§ Becoming a Queen of the Two Sicilies did Maria no favors.
By the time she got married to Francis, the Kingdom was already on shaky ground.
A quiet but deadly revolution had been bubbling under the surface, and in 1860, it finally arrived at their doorstep.
Needless to say, they were not prepared for it.

‚ù§ As enemies laid siege to the Kingdom, Francis‚Äô took a passive stance on the whole conflict.
Her husband‚Äôs spineless antics came as a shock to the bold and fiercely loyal warrior Queen.
Instead of taking charge, Francis started having panic attacks, and Maria was left to take care of the mess.

‚ù§ As the enemy troops slowly took over the Kingdom, Maria and Francis retreated to Gaeta with their men.
The seaside castle of Gaeta was far away from the dangers of Naples, and provided Francis with a sense of safety.
However, Maria was more intelligent than that, and knew that the incoming storm would mark the death of their empire.

‚ù§ Instead of relying on her good-for-nothing husband, she decided to take matters into her own hands and ended up on the front lines.
She rallied the troops, and cared for the wounded, earning the people's respect.
Beyond being brave, Maria was also full of mischief and wicked humor.
Once, in order to distract an approaching enemy fleet, she ordered her men to moon them with their bare bottoms!!

‚ù§ Maria Sophie‚Äôs enemies begrudgingly admitted her greatness.
One of her biggest rivals, Gabriel D‚ÄôAnnunzio, once referred to her as a ‚Äústern little Bavarian Eagle.‚Äù
Her horse riding lessons ended up serving her well in battle, as she fought alongside her people.
Not only that, but Maria also wielded a sword, as if she was born to be on the battlefield.

‚ù§ Tales of Maria‚Äôs fearlessness and tenacity in the face of war, spread all over Europe.
She was considered such a warrior queen, that she earned the flattering title ‚ÄúThe Modern Joan of Arc.‚Äù
That‚Äôs an impressive feat for a 19-year-old girl.

‚ù§ Despite Maria‚Äôs sacrifices on the battlefield, The Kingdom of Two Sicilies crumbled on 20th March 1861.
Maria and Francis escaped to Rome in peaceful exile, but this was only the beginning of the warrior queen‚Äôs incredible journey.

‚ù§ While they were exiled in Rome, Maria gave into temptation and committed the ultimate sin.
A handsome Belgian officer captured her heart.
In 1862, Maria discovered the consequences of giving in to her passions.
The queen was carrying her lover‚Äôs child, and she couldn‚Äôt even pass it off as the royal heir.

‚ù§ Maria‚Äôs influential family got wind of the brewing scandal, and immediately sprung into action.
The former queen was transported to the German palace, and it was agreed that Maria would secretly give birth to the baby.
Maria gave birth to her illegitimate daughter on 24th November (truncated)

Resolution is not the most important thing when conflict rears its ugly head. It‚Äôs definitely important, and you should always work towards resolution. But if you focus too much on it, you‚Äôll typically compromise your method to achieve it. One of the greatest lessons I‚Äôve learned in conflict is being more OK with things not being OK. In other words, being patient with the timing of the resolution. I‚Äôm not saying to avoid conflict, and I‚Äôm also not saying to stop pursuing resolution. But I am saying that sometimes we need to surrender the timing of when the resolution happens. Conflict resolution takes two people. And you can‚Äôt control the other person. When you try to control the other person to reach a resolution, you‚Äôre on your way to creating another issue to resolve! When you focus on respecting your spouse over the resolution, the resolution typically happens faster and more naturally. It might not happen in your timing, but when you prioritize respect, chances are it will happen. . . . #respect #conflict #conflictresolution #marriagetips #marriagerevolution #turnlovearound

SIRIUS by Olaf Stapledon. Subtitled: "A Fantasy of Love and Discord". Penguin Books | 1st U.K pb, 3rd impression | 188 pp. | ¬£0.30 | 1973. Cover illustration by David Pelham. Originally published in hc format in the U.K. by Secker & Warburg, 1944. First pb edition in the U.K. by Penguin Books, 1964. ‚ÄîBack cover text‚Äî SIRIUS is a tale of immense and tragic pathos in which Olaf Stapledon evokes the terrible loneliness of a dog born with the mind of a man. Thomas Trelone's life-work was to explore the possibilities of producing a superman by experimenting with hormone injections into various mammals. Sirius himself is infinitely the most successful of these trials. He is the only viable puppy born with the brain capacity of a human being, but he still has teh senses, the instincts, and the physique of a dog. Born at the same time as Plaxy, Thomas's youngest daughter, the child and puppy are brought up together, share the same lessons, and develop an intense understanding of one another's humanness and dogness. It is the inevitable conflict between Sirius's intellect and instincts and its effects upon the girl, Plaxy, which has produced one of the most moving of the 'Wonder Stories' we call Science Fiction.

On Tuesday, many media outlets rushed to amplify Hamas's claims about an Israeli airstrike on a Gaza hospital killing hundreds of Palestinians. Almost no part of the initial story turned out to be true. The blast was in the parking lot; it was caused by an errant Palestinian rocket, not an Israeli strike; and it's likely that the number of casualties was nowhere near what Hamas claimed. One of the most appalling journalistic failures around this story was Sky News's Anna Botting. In an interview with Netanyahu Senior Advisor Mark Regev, she made clear that she had abandoned even the pretense of objectivity or journalistic curiosity. After Regev denied that Israel targeted the hospital, she said, "You have the capability to cause utter devastation to the people of Gaza City. That‚Äôs what‚Äôs happened tonight. The real fact of it is whatever is the cause of this, it might be too late, the touch paper has already been lit, do you understand that?" In other words, the truth about the explosion was irrelevant to the question of who was to blame. This is appalling coming from someone whose job is supposed to be finding out the truth. Even after the full facts were known, Botting continued to blame Israel. In an interview with IDF spokesman Jonathan Conricus, she asked, "Do you accept though, that those people would not have been sheltering in the vicinity of a hospital like this if you hadn‚Äôt bombed them out of their homes?" That's a frankly outrageous question. Hamas started this war with its barbaric slaughter of innocent civilians on October 7. Botting has shown her true colors and her complete lack of journalistic integrity. She cannot be trusted to report on this conflict.

Solomon Islands Government acknowledge assistance from Australia in airlifting Solomon Islanders from Israel amidst conflict. The Solomon Islands Government has acknowledged the help of Australia in providing the safe departure of Solomon Islands nationals from Israel following the ongoing conflict in the area. The first 65 Solomon Islands nationals arrived in Sydney, Australia last night after they were transported out of Tel Aviv on board a Royal Australia Airforce flight on Tuesday 17th October bound for Dubai. Another 14 nationals were airlifted out of Tel Aviv on the 18 October and will be arriving in Brisbane at 22:20 tonight. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and External Trade in consultation with Prime Minister Office had been working closely with the Government of Australia through the High Commission in Honiara to facilitate the safe return of the Solomon Islanders who were attending the Feast of Tabernacles program. The Solomon Islands is grateful for the assistance rendered by the Government of Australia in providing safe passage for our nationals trapped in Israel after most commercial flights were disrupted since the conflict between Israel and Palestinian group Hamas began over a week ago. The Solomon Islands Mission representative in Australia welcomed the Solomon Islands nationals last night in Sydney and thanked the Government of Australia and their officials for the assistance. Apart from their safe passage, Australia is also making arrangement for overnight hotel accommodation in Sydney before the group will travel to Brisbane today (Thursday 19th October) in anticipation of their flight to the Solomon Islands. The first group will arrive in Honiara on Friday 20th October, while the second group will be home on Saturday 21st October 2023. ENDS////WITH PHOTOS CAPTIONS: 1. Yes, desire, passions, the whole emotional world breaks loose. Sex, power, and every devil in our nature gets loose when we become acquainted with the unconscious. Then you will suddenly see a new picture of yourself. That is why people are afraid and say there is no unconscious, like children playing hide-and-seek. A child goes behind a door and says, ‚ÄúNobody is behind this door; don‚Äôt look here!‚Äù And so we have two marvelous psychological theories that nothing is behind this door, don‚Äôt look here, this is nothing important. Those are apotropaic theories. But you will see that there is something, you must admit that there are such powers. Then you make an abstraction, you make marvelous abstract signs of it, and talk of it with only a sort of shy hinting. You speak euphemistically. As sailors never dared to say, ‚ÄúThis damned hell of a sea, this black sea that is always so stormy and smashes our ships!‚Äù They said, ‚ÄúThe welcoming benevolent sea . . .‚Äù‚Äîin order not to arouse those alarming impressions, or to irritate those dark wind demons. Instead of saying the archbishop of Canterbury, you say His Grace. You don‚Äôt say the pope has issued a very foolish encyclica, you say the Vatican. Or instead of speaking of those hellish liars, you say Wilhelm strasse, or Downing Street, or the Quai d‚ÄôOrsay. That is the euphemistic abstract way of putting things. Our science has the same purpose in using Latin or Greek words. It is a marvelous shield against the demons‚Äîthe demons are afraid of Greek because they do not understand it. And therefore we talk, as you have just demonstrated, in such an abstract way. So it is just that‚Äîyou get into the world of fire, where things become red-hot. After baptism you get right into hell‚Äîthat is the enantiodromia. And now comes the paradox of the East: it is also the fullness of jewels. But what is passion, what are emotions? There is the source of fire, there is the fullness of energy. A man who is not on fire is nothing: he is ridiculous, he is two-dimensional. He must be on fire even if he does make a fool of himself. A flame must burn somewhere, otherwise no light shines; there is no warmth, nothing. It is terribly awkward, sure enough; it is painful, full of conflict, apparently a mere waste of time‚Äîat all events, it is against reason. But that accursed Kundalini says, ‚ÄúIt is the fullness of jewels; there is the source of energy.‚Äù As Heraclitus aptly said: war is the father of all things. - Carl Jung (The Psychology of Kundalini Yoga. )

Starbucks and the union representing its U.S. workers filed lawsuits against each other on October 18, in a disagreement over a pro-Palestine post on X, formerly known as Twitter.

The tweet in question went up on the Starbucks Workers United (SWU) account on October 9, 2 days after the Israel-Gaza conflict began. It read, 'Solidarity with Palestine' and quote-tweeted an image of a bulldozer operated by Hamas tearing down a fence along the Gaza Strip. The post was deleted after 40 minutes.

In Starbucks‚Äô lawsuit, filed in federal court in Iowa, the coffee chain said that the pro-Palestinian post angered customers and tarnished the company‚Äôs reputation. It's suing for trademark infringement and seeking to have the union stop using its name, 'Starbucks Workers Union,' and its logo, which includes a green circle and resembles Starbucks' logo.

Starbucks has argued the name confuses customers, who take their anger about SWU‚Äôs stance out on store employees. The company said it received more than 1,000 complaints about the tweet and people spray-painted Stars of David and a swastika on the windows of a Rhode Island store.

There have also been calls for boycotts from politicians, including Sen. Rick Scott (R-FL). 'This is disgusting,' Scott tweeted on October 11 in reference to the union‚Äôs post. 'Every American should condemn the atrocities that Iran-backed Hamas terrorists committed in Israel. Boycott Starbucks until its leadership strongly denounces and takes action against this horrific support of terrorism.'

Starbucks' official statement, released on October 11, expressed sympathy for innocent people on both sides of the conflict. 'Starbucks unequivocally condemns acts of hate, terrorism and violence.'

SWU, which represents more than 9,000 workers at more than 360 stores, responded to the company‚Äôs lawsuit with its own filing in federal court. The union argued their X profile identifies it as a union. IT also noted that unions often use the company name of the workers they represent.

Even so, we cannot change the actions that have come before. We can only choose the reactions that have yet to come.

Embracing the ups and downs of relationships is one of the best ways to build harmony. Our attachment to fun, excitement, and perfection can lead us into the unreasonable idea that a relationship should be continuously pleasant. 

The reality is that human beings cannot constantly sustain such high energy levels, if we tried to, we would either fall into performative and untruthful behavior or we would burn out and crash. Like the seasons, we also go through phases, and this directly impacts how we show up. 

Especially when a relationship is open to growth, there may be times when one of you is moving through and unloading old hurt/trauma or in need of a slowing down period for proper integration of new wisdom. When two people can appreciate that moods vary and calmly communicate the reality of the moment they are in, it becomes easier to step up for each other and provide loving support. 

When two people are in close proximity there will eventually be some form of conflict that arises; how you handle conflicts over time can determine whether your connection becomes deeper or whether you start drifting apart.

Ego craves to win, but loving clarity seeks to understand. When you bring awareness to your ego, it loses its power and gives more space for your actions to become motivated by a loving clarity. In these difficult moments, you want to be fair and take turns describing your perspectives. 

It is especially helpful if you focus your narratives around how you felt as things transpired as opposed to just placing blame. You shouldn‚Äôt try to invalidate each other‚Äôs perspectives. Once it is clear how you both felt, the real work revolves around collectively figuring out how you can meet each other in the middle and move forward.

Obeying Jesus‚Äô command taught me several powerful truths we experience when we pray for people who have hurt us:

1. Prayer shields our hearts from bitterness. It gives us a verbal outlet for our pain, a way to begin releasing our resentment to God. It prevents righteous anger and real hurt from twisting into damaging bitterness.

2. Prayer humbles us. It reminds us that even when we have been hurt, we are imperfect and need grace too. It may even help us to consider the conflict from the other person‚Äôs perspective.

3. Prayer helps us resist the temptation to seek revenge. It reminds us that God loves justice and that we can trust Him to defend and protect us.

4. Prayer gives us peace while we wait for resolution. Praying strengthens our relationship with God during our relational conflict. We trust that God is working even when we can‚Äôt see or understand all He is doing.

If you‚Äôre embroiled in a conflict, wrestling with bitterness, or feeling hurt or confused by a strained relationship, Jesus‚Äô encouragement to pray for your enemy may provide the protection your heart needs. You can pray about your situation, and pray for the person with whom you are in conflict, every day ‚Äî even multiple times a day.

Feeling wounded by a friend‚Äôs refusal to accept your apology? You can pray about that.

Feeling afraid she may hurt more people if she doesn‚Äôt change? You can pray about that.

Longing to attempt reconciliation but not sure the other person will even speak to you? You can pray about that.

We can pray about all of it. God welcomes our requests, and He longs to help His children find forgiveness and unity (John 17:20-23).

It takes time, but when we commit to persistently praying for those who offend us, we give God the chance to work on their hearts ‚Äî and ours.

I can‚Äôt imagine getting my wounded loved one to a hospital only to have it bombed. 

I can‚Äôt help but think like a mother. Ordinary citizens are not the government. Regular neighbors are not the terrorist organization. Almost all of us are just daughters and sons and moms and dads and grandmas and grandpas and aunts and uncles, innocents, all. We want the same things: basic freedom, safety, and the possibility of goodness for our families. When I think about Palestinian and Israeli mothers going to bed tonight having lost their children, terrified of more violence, just normal people in normal towns, I weep. 

We aren‚Äôt the lawmakers, the legislators, the ambassadors, or the power brokers. Nor are we the terrorists, kidnappers, murderers, or abusers. Also notably, we aren‚Äôt the pundits, analysts, experts, or strategists. We are just the ordinary, global neighbors of the ordinary people of Palestine and Israel, and our tool is compassion. I wish with all my heart for stabilization, liberation, safety, and the end of war for our neighbors. I wish for free people living on free land. I wish all moms could put their babies to bed tonight without fear. 

In this grant round, @legacycollective has nominated Global Empowerment Mission supporting all refugees fleeing the region through Egypt. If we lose the capacity to care for families running for their lives, there is no hope for any of us. If you‚Äôd like to join us, I will put the link in stories. Comments off.

We call on our government to act now to bring the hostages home. Alive, healthy, and whole. It‚Äôs possible. Our government cannot give up on the hostages. Our government cannot run from their responsibility to these people. 200 hostages in Gaza. It‚Äôs possible, it‚Äôs necessary, it‚Äôs a must that we make every effort to free them.

Around 200 men, women, and children were kidnapped into the Gaza Strip at the hands of Hamas and Islamic Jihad. Every one of these hostages is a whole world, a world unto themselves. And they are all part of families and communities - parents, siblings, partners, children, friends. 200 worlds. It‚Äôs forbidden for us to give up on them.

We can save Avinatan, Andrey, Segev, Almog, Ofek, Eitan, Tamar, Eden, Avigail, Rom, Vivian, Moran - we can save them and so many others. We can bring back peace of heart to so many parents, siblings, families, and friends. We can release them and we must release them. They‚Äôre trusting us.

At the moment, we know almost nothing about their status, mainly because Hamas is preventing anyone from seeing them - including the Red Cross. Parents are panicking for their children who may not have their inhalers, children worried for their parents who don‚Äôt have their medicines, people on tenterhooks waiting for news on their loved one‚Äôs lives. They know that the mass-scale bombings in Gaza affect the hostages, too.

We are calling on the government of Israel, on US President Joe Biden, on the countries of the world and our Palestinian counterparts - to anyone who wants to advance a political solution and work to end the occupation and the conflict - to take action to secure the peace, safety, and return of the hostages.

Resistance to occupation doesn‚Äôt justify harming innocent civilians, just as Israel cannot justify harming civilians in Gaza. It‚Äôs our responsibility to oppose acts that hurt Israeli civilians, just as we oppose acts that hurt Palestinian civilians. Sooner or later, some sort of deal will come. But time is not on our side. The time to bring them home is now. Free the hostages now.

A senior official at the US State Department issued his resignation on Wednesday evening, citing the Biden administration‚Äôs approach to the Israel-Palestine conflict.

‚ÄúLet me be clear: Hamas‚Äô attack on Israel was not just a monstrosity; it was a monstrosity of monstrosities,‚Äù Josh Paul said in a letter, which was posted on X by Brian Finucane, a senior adviser at Crisis Group.

‚ÄúBut I believe to the core of my soul that the response Israel is taking, and with it the American support both for that response, and for the status quo of the occupation, will only lead to more and deeper suffering for both the Israeli and the Palestinian people - and is not in the long term American interest.‚Äù

Paul worked for more than 10 years in the State Department‚Äôs Political-Military Affairs bureau, which is in charge of approving arms transfers to other countries.

In an interview with Huffington Post, Paul said that he resigned because he "couldn‚Äôt shift anything".

Biden has been clear in stating that he will support Israel unequivocally as it takes action against Palestinian armed groups in Gaza, which on 7 October launched a surprise attack on Israel.

The war has so far killed more than 3,000 Palestinians, including around 1,000 children and 1,000 women, while also killing more than 1,400 Israelis.

MEE reported last week that the White House‚Äôs phrasing of any calls for a ceasefire were ‚Äúrepugnant‚Äù, sending a chilling message to progressive lawmakers and anti-war activists.

The Biden administration is currently drafting a major foreign aid bill that would include $10bn for Israel. In addition to the aid package, the US has also deployed two carrier strike groups to the Eastern Mediterranean and has readied 2,000 American troops to be deployed in order to support Israel, as the country readies for a ground invasion of Gaza.

‚ÄúI cannot work in support of a set of major policy decisions, including rushing more arms to one side of the conflict, that I believe to be shortsighted, destructive, unjust, and contradictory to the very values that we publicly espouse,‚Äù Paul said further in his letter.

üåç Hello Dear Friends, Cultural Creatives & Seekers Everywhere, 

War does not determine who is right, it determines who is left.

The world is currently trying to come to terms with the inhumane atrocities carried out by both sides of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. Around the globe, citizens are rallying in a concerted effort to bring an end to the barbaric nature of planetary violence and war in today‚Äôs modern world. On the horizon, I see a second opportunity is now arising wherein global civilization is once again coalescing and demanding an end to war.

War, violence, and division only perpetuate a cycle of suffering. We must now begin to emphasize that it is not our differences, but our common humanity that must come to the forefront. Through nurturing compassion and empathy, we will come to recognize the notion that the well-being of one  is intrinsically linked to the well-being of all. This is the first step towards healing the world.

In times of crisis, we come together to support one another, regardless of our backgrounds. This ability to unite must extend beyond moments of crisis to become a way of life. It is my fervent hope that we can create a world where differences are celebrated, where conflicts are resolved through dialogue and understanding, and where the power of our shared humanity prevails. The Israeli-Palestinian conflict is a painful reminder of the work that lies ahead, but it is not an insurmountable challenge.

Let us commit to educating ourselves about the complexities of this issue, to supporting peace initiatives, and to spreading the message of unity. By doing so, we can honor our shared humanity and work toward a future where conflicts no longer define our world.
 
With Peace, Love & Light, 
Bruce

Years ago I worked in a Romanian orphanage in my Gap Year. It was a well intentioned but ultimately selfish act. The time came when I had to leave, which meant abandoning the (already traumatised) kids all over again. 
@hopeandhomesforchildren educated me about the profound damage #orphanages have on children; and that of the 5.4 million children confined to institutions around the World, 80% of them aren‚Äôt in fact orphans at all. They have a living relative, who, with the right support, can look after them.

I will always regret not returning to find Mirela (pictured) sooner. When I did find her ten years later, she was tied to a radiator, and had lost the ability to speak and walk - such was the neglect, and lack of love.

I will always be grateful to our #f1 #family (esp @pirelli_motorsport) for helping me build a home for her and her siblings.

No kid should grow up in an institution, help us reunite those separated from their families due to conflict, poverty, trafficking and lack of resource, by following @hopeandhomesforchildren 

And please don‚Äôt make the mistake that I did, by visiting orphanages and propping up often corrupt and exploitative institutions - which treat children like commodities. Elephant herds are in a constant state of motion. To find the huge amounts of water and food they need to survive, these massive mammals must keep moving. In Botswana's Okavango Delta ‚Äì home to the world's largest elephant population ‚Äì life is governed by the seasonal ebb and flow of annual floodwaters. Herds trek across this vast swathe of bushveld in great numbers as they follow ancient migratory pathways etched into the earth by generation after generation of grey giants. Although populations are relatively stable in this part of the world, herds are still threatened by conflict with humans as they stray out of protected areas. A recent survey indicates a high mortality rate for elephants in the Kavango Zambezi Transfrontier Conservation Area (KAZA TFCA). The reasons for this are not yet fully understood, but factors such as poaching, habitat loss, human-elephant conflict and disease may play a role. One thing is clear: if we hope to peacefully share space with elephants, we need to find conservation solutions that benefit both people and wildlife. ‚Å£‚Å£

On November 29, 1947 the United Nations adopted Resolution 181 (also known as the Partition Resolution) that would divide Great Britain‚Äôs former Palestinian mandate into Jewish and Arab states in May 1948 when the British mandate was scheduled to end. Under the resolution, the area of religious significance surrounding Jerusalem would remain a corpus separatum under international control administered by the United Nations.

Although the United States backed Resolution 181, the U.S. Department of State recommended the creation of a United Nations trusteeship with limits on Jewish immigration and a division of Palestine into separate Jewish and Arab provinces but not states. The State Department, concerned about the possibility of an increasing Soviet role in the Arab world and the potential for restriction by Arab oil producing nations of oil supplies to the United States, advised against U.S. intervention on behalf of the Jews. Later, as the date for British departure from Palestine drew near, the Department of State grew concerned about the possibility of an all-out war in Palestine as Arab states threatened to attack almost as soon as the UN passed the partition resolution.

Despite growing conflict between Palestinian Arabs and Palestinian Jews and despite the Department of State‚Äôs endorsement of a trusteeship, Truman ultimately decided to recognize the state Israel.

DOD assets in the Red Sea, Iraq and Syria responded to missile and drone attacks over the past two days, as U.S. service members look to deter groups from using the Israel-Hamas war as an opportunity to launch conflict that could engulf the region, Pentagon Press Secretary Air Force Brig. Gen. Pat Ryder said today.

Ryder also spelled out the steps Secretary of Defense Lloyd J. Austin III has taken to strengthen DOD posture in the region to bolster regional deterrence efforts.

Ryder said the crew of the guided missile destroyer USS Carney operating in the northern Red Sea earlier today shot down three land attack cruise missiles and several drones launched by Houthi forces in Yemen. "This action was a demonstration of the integrated air and missile defense architecture that we built in the Middle East and that we are prepared to utilize whenever necessary to protect our partners and our interests," he said. 

There were no casualties. 

"We cannot say for certain what these missiles and drones were targeting, but they were launched heading north along the Red Sea potentially towards targets in Israel," the general said. 

Ryder also detailed drone attacks on U.S. facilities in Syria and Iraq. The al-Tanf garrison in Syria was targeted by two drones on Oct. 18. "U.S. and coalition forces engaged one drone destroying it while the other drone impacted the base resulting in minor injuries to coalition forces," Ryder said. All of the injured returned to duty. 

At the same time, early warning systems indicated a possible threat approaching the airbase at al-Assad. Base personnel sheltered in place as a protective measure. "Though no attack occurred, sadly, a U.S. civilian contractor suffered a cardiac episode while sheltering and passed away shortly thereafter," Ryder said.

Separately in northern Iraq, U.S. forces engaged and destroyed a drone resulting in no injuries or damage. 

Ryder said he will not detail what the American response to these provocations will be. "I will say that we will take all necessary actions to defend U.S. and coalition forces against any threat," he said.

In the heart of one of the world's most enduring conflicts lies Gaza, a place that has come to symbolize the deeply entrenched struggle between Palestinians and Israelis. The Gaza Strip is a tiny enclave with heavily controlled borders that is home to over two million Palestinians, and its people endure hardships that few outsiders can comprehend.

The current conflict, which was initiated by a terrorist organization, is but the latest installment in a cycle of violence that in its most recent phase was initiated in 1948 with the establishment of the State of Israel. Gaza has in fact been built up, destroyed and repopulated by a long list of conquerors and empires over a period of more than one hundred generations. For these thousands of years, a deep-seated karmic pattern of violence and vengeance has been reinforced, a pattern that promotes more of the same in each ensuing generation and discourages any kind of meaningful arrangement that could bring a lasting peace.

The deliberate torture, rape, and murder of hundreds of helpless Israeli civilians, with children at school, the elderly and babies specifically targeted, was a heinous crime. Hamas did this to deliberately provoke an overreaction, one that they are praying will be so excessive that another generation will become sufficiently radicalized and fanatical to perpetuate the pattern. My first impressions of Saranda, Albania: ‚ÄúUhh this looks...interesting.‚Äù Which is my polite way of saying, ‚ÄúWhat on earth is going on here?‚Äù

After we got docked in Saranda, I walked by abandoned buildings, dodged broken glass along pseudo -sidewalks (if we can even call them that), all while catching just the most delightful whiffs of fishy garbage.

Enter my newfound friend Ari, a local Albanian guide and historian, basically the ringleader of my Albanian odyssey and why I wanted to give Albania a genuine chance.

With Ari, I got immersed into the best of Albania‚Äôs heritage‚Äì his family rolled out the red carpet of Albanian hospitality. His wife had the day off of work so she toured around with us. His mother-in-law greeted me with the biggest hug and kiss, as if I was their long-lost family member.

Shaped by thousands of years of conflict and resilience, Ari taught me so much about the Illyrians, and showed me how much Albania has changed since emerging from a cruel and repressive regime in the 1990s. We talked about the good and the bad as we drove around to his favorite beaches, ancient sites, and delicious food spots.

Moral of the story: First impressions can be deceiving.

A heartfelt thanks to Ari and fam, who laid the foundation for an epic summer living and working remotely from Albania.

'Lt "Lucky" Edwin Wright, just over 19 years old, just returned from his 39th mission over Munster. He got hit by flak but continued on his mission dropped his bombs, did a spot of strafing and returned. When he got back he found a hole 8 inches in diameter through his 11 inch diameter prop blade, caused by a direct hit from an ‚Äòack ack‚Äô shell. 
___
If the shell had deviated an inch and a half either side, his blade would have severed and he would have been brought down. This is the 6th time that Wright has been hit by Flak and is now known as ‚ÄúLucky Wright‚Äù. He has 5 and a half months of combat to his credit and 39 missions.‚Äô - Roger LIFE
___
Edwin Wright flew a total of 88 missions in P-47 Thunderbolts over Europe during the Second World War. He left the Army in 1946 and was again called up for the Korean Conflict in 1950. He retired from the U.S. Air Force as a Major. Edwin Wright passed away in 1959, from lung cancer, age 34.

Waari Singbul Network | Oct 19, 2023

Imphal: Owing to the unceasing ethnic strife besetting Manipur, Ningol Chakkouba, the biggest festival of Manipuri women may not be celebrated in earnest.¬†Noticeably, many individuals and locals organisations in the state have taken their decision not to celebrate Chakkouba this time.

Hordes of¬†Meitei civil bodies of the state also appealed to forgo the festival that falls on November 15 taking into account¬†the unstable state of affairs triggered by the violence.

On Chakkouba day, the age-old festival, Meitei women, particularly the married ones, in their best traditional attires, move to their natal homes and enjoy multi dishes with their parents and siblings.

With simple gifts and blessings given by their parents and brothers, the Ningols (women) return home with high spirits. Entertainment programmes like music concerts, Shumang Leela (courtyard theatre) etc. are also held on Chakkouba day.

The festival has encompassed other communities since the last few decades, standing as testimony of love, unity and integration in the state. An irony to what is happening with over 175 people killed, 1108 injured and rendered around 60,000 homeless and sheltered in relief camps. Over thousands of houses and other properties have been destroyed since the ethnic conflict broke on May 3.

‚ÄúHad there been no violence in our state we would have by now planned everything for the ensuing Ningol Chakkouba like¬† the fish menu for the family feasting and the simple gift items to be given to
our married daughters and beloved¬† Ningols (women),‚Äù said Saikhom Ongbi Tombi Devi, a resident of Thangmeiband area in Imphal West district.

‚ÄúWhen the bereaved families are weeping for their near and dear ones killed, injured and maimed¬† in the unceasing conflict, when the people whose houses and properties were destroyed by miscreants and taking refuge at relief camps and when the people are bearing the brunt of the public unrest, there will¬† be no happiness in Ningol Chakkouba. Hence, we have decided to forgo the festival this time,‚Äù she added.

India's aviation industry has been experiencing a resurgence, with air traffic reaching new highs and indicating a promising outlook for pilots who weathered the storm of the pandemic. However, beneath the surface, a less rosy picture emerges as the relationship between pilots and airline management becomes increasingly strained, particularly within Air India, which underwent a change in ownership almost two years ago.
Since Tata Sons took over Air India, the relationship between the airline's pilots and the new management has hit an all-time low. It is no secret that senior pilots have often struggled to find a sense of belonging within the organisation they serve, given the unique nature of their profession. 
Senior pilots in Air India have been vocal about their grievances, frequently sharing their concerns on platforms like WhatsApp. Insiders suggest that the "diminishing status" of pilots and crew members has been "a deliberate tactic aimed at alienating these critical staff members". 

Insiders from the airline also allege that the pilots were displaced from high-ranking roles, including positions like chief of operations, which subsequently ignited a conflict with the management.
While the Tata management has concentrated on the aesthetics and quality of service, there appears to be a pressing need to address deeper issues within the organisation.
Sources from the ministry of civil aviation (MOCA), assert that Tata should have replaced the old management team with a fresh one soon after taking control. The retained management, with its existing ways of doing things, is viewed as a destabilising influence, continuing to fuel the infighting within the airline.
Air India has long suffered from the existence of factional camps, each often motivated by self-interest rather than the airline's well-being. Retaining the old management has inadvertently perpetuated these divisions, intensifying the adversarial relationship between different employee groups and management.

Pakistan Thursday dispatched the first consignment carrying relief assistance to Gaza as Israel's indiscriminate bombardment continues on the Hamas-ruled strip, killing thousands and displacing millions.

The relief assistance, carrying one thousand winter tents, four thousand blankets, and three tonnes of medicines, will reach Palestine via Egypt in a chartered aircraft, the Foreign Office said in a statement.

Israel's unabated airstrikes on Gaza have claimed nearly 3,500 lives while thousands of others are injured. Entire city blocks have been levelled, water, food, and power have been cut off, and over one million people have been displaced.

Hamas's October 7 attack on Israel has claimed more than 1,400 lives ‚Äî and the conflict has set off a wave of fury across the Middle East against Israel and its Western allies.

At the media briefing today, FO spokesperson Mumtaz Zahra Baloch said Pakistan remains deeply concerned about the situation of "our Palestinian brothers and sisters" in Gaza.

‚ÄúWe strongly condemn the Israeli aggression and blockade, particularly the recent attack on a Gaza hospital. Israel's actions violate international humanitarian and human rights law,‚Äù she added.

The FO spokesperson further said deliberate attacks against civilian targets constitute war crimes and crimes against humanity.

‚ÄúWe call for an immediate ceasefire; an end to the siege of Gaza; and the facilitation of humanitarian corridors for unrestricted relief supplies.‚Äù

The development came as Israel agreed on a deal for an initial 20 trucks carrying relief goods to cross the shuttered Rafah crossing from Egypt into Gaza, with the first deliveries expected Friday at the earliest.

More than 100 trucks carrying aid goods have been queued for days on the Egyptian side of the Rafah border crossing, the only entry or exit point to Gaza not controlled by Israel.

Cairo has so far kept it closed, pointing to repeated Israeli strikes near the crossing and voicing fears that Israel may be hoping to permanently drive Palestinians out and into Egypt¬¥s Sinai desert.

The Albanese government will expedite a new national racism strategy amid rising community tensions triggered by the war between Israel and Hamas, and the defeat of the Indigenous voice to parliament referendum last Saturday.

The minister for multicultural affairs, Andrew Giles, told Guardian Australia‚Äôs politics podcast there is a ‚Äúrenewed sense of urgency‚Äù about launching the new anti-racism campaign ‚Äúgiven the events of recent weeks‚Äù.

Asked how concerned he was about social cohesion in Australia in the wake of the polarising referendum campaign and domestic anxieties about the Middle East conflict, Giles replied: ‚ÄúI‚Äôm very concerned.‚Äù

The government has been working with the Australian Human Rights Commission to set the foundations of an anti-racism strategy. Giles said ‚Äúsome research has gone into how we best go about it and how we best engage Australians who, in the context of busy lives, may not have the bandwidth to think through some of these issues in detail‚Äù.

‚ÄúI think that is a big lesson of recent politics around the world ‚Äì that we have got to understand how all the pressures and dimensions of an individual‚Äôs life impact on their willingness or capacity to engage in issues ‚Ä¶ we‚Äôve got to be where people are, not where we want them to be.‚Äù

Giles said in order to be persuasive, the government had to consider how best to connect people with ‚Äúexperiences that may not be part of their lives‚Äù.

October 19, 2005, Haifa Israel (18 years ago today)
‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®
Ori & I took Ruby to meet her maternal great grandparents, Bella & Isaac, upon her turning one years old. We felt it was important to make this trip since they were already in their 90‚Äôs.
‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®
On this particular day we spent the afternoon just chatting with them. Their English was not great and my Hebrew, nonexistent, so Ori acted as translator and I was the one asking the questions. 
‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®
Ori‚Äôs grandfather shared about how they fled Poland right before the Holocaust and how lucky they were to survive. Sadly, their siblings were not so lucky and did not make it. 
‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®
I wanted to post this photo and have it live on my feed because it is part of my children‚Äôs story, it is their lineage. Their grandparents, (Ori‚Äôs parents), were first generation Israelis. I cannot help but think how devastated Issac & Bella, people that escaped the Holocaust, would feel about the current state of the world. 
‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®
The internet has gone mad with people becoming geopolitical experts overnight, even though they have never been to this region nor have any affiliation with it. There is name calling, sharing of stories just for clicks or for their agenda of proving they are right before they have even verified the story or the source. There are college students ripping down hostage posters in some sort of twisted act of social justice thinking some how ‚Äúthey deserved it‚Äù. There was an innocent 6 year old Palestinian American stabbed 26 times in a hate crime. 
‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®
This is dividing us and making an already highly fraught world, more broken. We cannot become numb to our humanity and create a competition of suffering. We need to keep educating ourselves, (me included), so we expand our hearts to everyone involved in this conflict, as we are all connected.
‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®
Some may ask, why it is my place to even post this. I guess in my own depth of sadness, I am hoping that I could potentially have an effect on some (even one person would be great) to consider the complexity of this situation and to strive for UNITY, UNDERSTANDING, EMPATHY & PEACE‚Ä¶I know that is a long way off but we need to start some where‚Ä¶.TOGETHER WE RISE ü´∂üèº

The Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, Rishi Sunak is set to embark on a visit to Israel later on Thursday, where he will meet with the top leaders to discuss the country's ongoing war with Hamas, and express solidarity, Reuters reported citing the UK PM's office.

According to his office, Sunak will meet Israel's PM Benjamin Netanyahu and President Isaac Herzog and will share his condolences for the loss of life in Israel and Gaza as a result of the October 7 attack on Israel.

"Every civilian death is a tragedy. And too many lives have been lost following Hamas' horrific act of terror," Sunak said in a statement ahead of his visit, according to Reuters.

Moreover, as per Reuters report, Sunak will call for the opening up of a route to allow humanitarian aid into Gaza as soon as possible and to make it possible for British nationals trapped in Gaza to depart.

Questions arose when Pink‚Äôs dancers were seen flying blue and white ‚Äúpoi‚Äù flags on long poles. ‚ÄúI am getting many threats because people mistakenly believe I am flying Israeli flags in my show. I am not,‚Äù Pink tweeted. I have been using Poi flags since the beginning of this tour. Israel has blamed Palestinian Islamic Jihad for a deadly blast at a hospital in Gaza City Tuesday night.
 
Hundreds of people were reported killed in the explosion at al-Ahli Arab Baptist Hospital in Gaza City, which the Israel Defense Forces said was caused by a failed rocket launch by the group. Two U.S. officials also told ABC News the Pentagon independently concluded the blast was likely caused by an errant Palestinian Islamic Jihad rocket that fell short of its target.
 
Palestinian officials are claiming it was the result of an Israeli airstrike.
 
Like Hamas, Palestinian Islamic Jihad is a Gaza militant group involved in the conflict and has claimed to have taken Israelis hostages.
 
Islamic Jihad, the smaller of the two groups, is considered to be more extreme and is singularly devoted to fighting Israel, while Hamas also has sociopolitical functions as the governing body of Gaza.

A sizeable number attended the prayers with their children in response to the organizers‚Äô appeal to the community to express solidarity and make dua for the safety of the people who are in distress.

Apart from Qunoot-e-Nazila prayers, several silent protests or flash protests are being regularly organised in Hyderabad in the aftermath of the Israel-Hamas-Hezbollah conflict that started this month.

A flash protest was also held recently at Shahalibanda. Another small silent protest was held near Charminar with youth holding placards standing silently to express their solidarity.

What are Qunoot e Nazila prayers?

Qunoot-e-Nazila is a special prayer by Muslims performed during calamities that befall the community. It is preferable to perform it during Fajr prayers (namaz before dawn) but can be performed during any five obligatory prayers.

Inzamam-ul-Haq, the former Pakistan cricket captain, is reportedly considering stepping down from his role as chief selector due to disagreements with the Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB).

Sources suggest that Inzamam is dissatisfied with the appointment of Shahid Anwar as the head coach of the U19 men's team, as he had advocated for former Pakistan cricketer Mohammad Yousaf to be given the position.
This is not the first instance of conflict between Inzamam and the PCB, as they have had differences in the past as well. Recently, Inzamam had signed a contract worth Rs2.5 million per month with the PCB.

However, the PCB has refuted these claims, with a spokesperson stating that Inzamam had actively participated in the selection process for the U19 men's team and the women's A team, and they had no knowledge of any discord between Inzamam and the board.

Earlier in the month, Inzamam was appointed as the chairman of the Junior Men's Cricket Selection Committee, adding to his existing responsibilities as the head of the senior selection committee. The senior selection committee includes Tauseef Ahmed, Wajahatullah Wasti, and Wasim Haider, while the junior selection committee consists of Aamer Nazir, Javed Hayat, Mahmood Hamid, Naveed Latif, Salman Ahmed, and Sanaullah Baloch.

In a separate development, former captain Mohammad Hafeez recently announced his resignation from the PCB Technical Committee via a post on X (formerly known as Twitter), expressing his gratitude to chairman Zaka Ashraf and conveying his best wishes to Pakistan cricket. Hafeez's decision to step down from the committee came after a brief tenure of just under two months.

Prime Minister Narendra Modi on Wednesday expressed shock at the tragic loss of lives at the al-Ahli Hospital in Gaza on Tuesday night, stating that "civilian casualties in the ongoing conflict are a matter of serious and continuing concern" and that "those involved should be held responsible".

Reacting to the reports that at least 500 people lost their lives in an explosion at the Saza hospital, the Prime Minister offered India's "heartfelt condolences to the families of the victims and prayers for the speedy recovery of those injured".

While the Palestinian foreign ministry reportedly blamed Israel for the horrific attack and termed it a "cold-blooded massacre", Israeli ambassador to India Naor Gilon on Wednesday said that the explosion at the al-Ahli Hospital in Gaza was due to a rocket fired by the Palestinian Islamic Jihad (PIJ) group.

The Israeli ambassador said: "al-Ahli hospital was hit by a rocket from the Palestinian Islamic jihad. Since the beginning of the fighting, more than 450 Palestinian-shot rockets have fallen inside the Gaza Strip. They try to hit our children, but on the way, they hit their own children. The international poison machine immediately accuses Israel. It's really a pity that many around the world are cooperating with them. But, in our technological world, everything is documented, and we have clear-cut evidence that it was a Palestinian Islamic Jihad rocket."

At least 100 Israelis have been arrested for social media posts supporting Palestinians in Gaza and 70 remain in detention, according to a legal advocacy group in the country. Adalah, which represents Arab Israelis in human rights cases, said the arrests are part of an unprecedented crackdown on freedom of expression in Israel.

"We‚Äôre seeing things we didn‚Äôt see before," Adi Mansour, an attorney in Adalah‚Äôs civil rights unit, said in an interview. "There‚Äôs a change in the perception of what is allowed and what is prevented."

Police arrested Dalal Abu Amneh, a prominent Palestinian-Israeli singer, for "incitement" after her social media team posted a Palestinian flag with the caption: "There is no victor but God," her lawyer told The New Arab.

Mansour said that others were arrested for posts that consisted of Koran verses, prayers for the people of Gaza and political analysis of Israeli military operations. He said that so far nobody had been charged by prosecutors, but that police had held many of them in detention for several days.

Instagram users are accusing the social network of purposefully censoring posts in support of Palestine ‚Äì underscoring longstanding concerns about unfair moderation as war rages in Gaza.

Hena Mustafa, an Instagram user with 866 followers based in New York City, said that since she began posting about developments in Palestine as Israel mounted its siege in the past week, her Stories ‚Äì photos and videos that disappear after 24 hours ‚Äì have been receiving ‚Äúsignificantly less views‚Äù. Friends and followers have messaged Mustafa to tell her that her posts are no longer appearing at the top of their Instagram feeds, her name has become unsearchable on the social network, and they are unable to interact with her posts.

Hundreds of others have shared similar experiences, said Nadim Nashif, founder and director of social media watchdog group 7amleh, the Arab Center for Social Media Advancement, which has been tracking the issue. 7amleh and others suspect the platform is shadow banning, or demoting content related to the conflict in the algorithm.

‚ÄúUnfortunately, shadow banning is just one of the many ways in which we have seen Palestinian content silenced and censored over the last week,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúThis has been a trend of Meta in times of crisis, and we saw a significant spike of Palestinians and allies reporting limited reach and errors with content they posted about the ongoing crisis in Palestine.‚Äù
Meta said in a statement that ‚Äúit is never our intention to suppress a particular community or point of view‚Äù, but that due to ‚Äúhigher volumes of content being reported‚Äù surrounding the ongoing conflict, ‚Äúcontent that doesn‚Äôt violate our policies may be removed in error‚Äù. The company additionally attributed some issues to glitches in its algorithmic moderation system that reduced the reach of posts ‚Äúequally around the globe‚Äù ‚Äì regardless of subject matter.

In a move sparking international concern, Azerbaijani authorities have revealed their ambitious plan to settle 140,000 Azerbaijanis in the Republic of Artsakh (Nagorno-Karabakh) by 2026, a decision that has raised serious questions about the rights and properties of the indigenous Armenian inhabitants. Emin Huseynov, the special representative of the president of Azerbaijan, made this announcement, as reported by APA.
The timing and scale of this resettlement plan have alarmed many, given the recent history of the region. It's noteworthy that the number of Azerbaijanis proposed to be settled mirrors the quantity of indigenous Armenians who fled Nagorno-Karabakh ‚Äî 100,000 during Azerbaijan's military aggression in September 2020 and approximately 40,000 who chose not to return after the 44-day war later that year.

What intensifies the controversy is the Azerbaijani authorities' apparent willingness to resettle a substantial population in Nagorno-Karabakh while failing to address the resettlement of previously occupied territories over the past three years. This decision raises concerns about the intentions of settling Azerbaijanis in homes once belonging to forcibly displaced Armenians, potentially leading to property disputes and human rights violations.

The fact that prior to the recent conflict, the number of Azerbaijanis residing in Nagorno-Karabakh was significantly lower has not deterred the Azerbaijani authorities from pursuing their resettlement agenda.
The international community watches closely as concerns grow over the potential ramifications of this decision. Questions about the protection of property rights, the displacement of indigenous populations, and the implications for regional stability have now taken center stage. The fate of Nagorno-Karabakh's future hangs in the balance, raising critical questions about the rights and livelihoods of its former indigenous Armenian inhabitants.

üìö Unsealed Covers : A Decade of the Constitution, the Courts and the State.

Book Blurb:

In Unsealed Covers, Gautam Bhatia provides a snapshot of the Indian judiciary between 2014 and 2023. The 2014 general election saw the installation of the first majority non-coalition government in many decades (the NDA). The 2019 general election saw its return with a greater majority. It is commonly accepted that the NDA years have generated significant conflict within and around various democratic institutions meant to act as checks and balances against majoritarian power.

One of the most important theatres of conflict has been the judiciary-in particular, the Supreme Court. Critics have distinguished the Supreme Court's past assertive record with its quiescent and sometimes facilitative attitude towards the NDA government(s). Unsealed Covers provides a unique terrain where the actions of the judiciary and its relationship with the government are examined in terms of evolution and chronology. It also comments on some of the most important judgments of the past decade.

üåôThe Half Moonüåô

‚ÄúNo two people ever love each other the same way.‚Äù

Have you ever wanted to beg a person to stay yet yell at them to get the hell out? I know I have.

The same happens to Malcolm Gephardt when his wife Jess decides to leave on Halloween night because they need a break. After a tumultuous few years of trying everything to have a baby, Malcolm‚Äôs thrown in the towel & she‚Äôs unable to cope. Having children is her ultimate dream, but Malcolm has his own ‚Äúbaby‚Äù to worry about. His bar,The Half Moon.

‚ÄúHe should have followed her that day‚Ä¶should have stopped her from getting in her car & talked everything out with her. But he‚Äôd just let her go. Because he was shocked‚Ä¶Because his feelings were hurt‚Ä¶Because he didn‚Äôt know what to say.‚Äù

They had two very different ways of handling stress, disappointment, conflict‚Äî

‚Äú[Jess] wanted a concrete solution‚Ä¶wanted a cure for grief & wanted someone to tell her where to find it.‚Äù

‚ÄúThe growing sense that life was passing her by & if she didn‚Äôt do something she‚Äôd leave nothing behind to prove she was even there.‚Äù

‚ÄúHe used to ask himself what he was going to do, but the question was too large, & he had no answer, so at some point he decided to just get through each day.‚Äù

As a happy-go-lucky bartender, soon to be bar-owner, Malcolm is impulsive & jumps on what he wants. He doesn‚Äôt think of repercussions or anyone but himself. Whereas Jess, an established lawyer, takes time to sort through facts, pros & cons; how a decision effects their joint lives. All opportunities well thought out.

The two also move on without each other differently. While Malcolm keeps to himself, sticks to his routine & thinks about what he could‚Äôve done different. Jess moves on with another person, perhaps just to see how it feels to live differently. 

‚ÄúShe was the voice in his head even when she wasn‚Äôt right in front of him.‚Äù

This book is a true testament of a couple trying to survive through the devastation of infertility. 

This was a good book‚Ä¶.but S-L-O-W. Also, third person POV isn‚Äôt my fave.

üí≠What‚Äôs the last book you read that you enjoyed but it took quite some time to read because of the pacing?
