Few people understand their anger or what to do with it.

We‚Äôve worked with many people in psychotherapy who have been denying their anger for decades. But repressing angry emotions is not good or helpful.

Anger is a God-given emotion. We feel angry when our will is crossed or when we‚Äôre afraid that we won‚Äôt get what we want.

Anger is not bad, it‚Äôs a natural human emotion.

Think of anger like a headache: it signals to us that something is wrong and needs attention. So if we are wise then we deal with the underlying problem‚Äîand hopefully that frees us of our anger headache!

Maybe you‚Äôre not saying no to someone or something when it is important to do so. Maybe you‚Äôre overloaded and not communicating your stress. Or you‚Äôve been hurt and need empathy.

It‚Äôs always helpful to be aware of all our emotions, including anger. The key is how we deal with our anger.

When we‚Äôre angry we may lose our temper, be passive-aggressive, or convert anger into guilt. Or we may stuff anger and live with resentment‚Äîperhaps we feel we need our anger to protect us or to give us power.

But to hold anger is to let it live in your body like cancer and it‚Äôll show up in a number of unhealthy ways.

So what can we do with our anger?

God wants us to be honest about the anger we feel when we‚Äôve been mistreated or our will has been crossed in some other way.

So for all of us, it‚Äôs important that we learn to listen to our angry feelings, express them in a safe place, speak the truth in love, set boundaries, and forgive people who offend us.

Practically, here are 3 steps to help you do this:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Be emotionally honest. Verbalize your situation of conflict and angry feelings to God and a safe friend.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Set boundaries. Verbalize your limits and ask for what you need so you won‚Äôt be mistreated again.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Submit to God. Entrust justice to God by letting go of your anger and forgiving the other person. Ask the Lord to help you do the next right and loving thing.

For more help with anger and other painful emotions, check out our new book, "Healthy Feelings, Thriving Faith"

With his daughter Rana, Abdulsamad adds flowers to the graves of the five family members he lost during the earthquake: his daughter, Ziba, 18; his son, Arif, 2; his wife Bibi Gul, 35; and two in-laws. Seven-year-old Rana was outside playing when the quake ‚Äì one of four in the span of a week ‚Äì hit. Now she collects dirt for the graves, and goes through the family remaining belongings to find what can be salvaged, picking up chickpeas one by one, while her father digs in the rubbles. 
I guess it‚Äôs impossible to convey how heart wrenching the situation of the families was; and how hard the future will be.
Like most of Zendajan district, the community of Seyad Aab village was already struggling after decades of conflict and repetitive droughts. Now the village has been almost completely destroyed and no one knows how the remaining inhabitants will survive.
¬†
The village is one of the worst hit but not an exception, thousands have died across several districts of Herat Province this month in the four earthquakes, and the loved ones who survived are left with nothing. More than 43.000 people have been directly affected in Herat province.
Although it wasn‚Äôt hit like the districts, in Herat city, people were sleeping in tents for fear another earthquakes would make their homes fall. Hospitals are overwhelmed. Humanitarian aid insufficient while thousands have no more home and the winter cold is settling.
¬†
I really have no words to describe how immense the pain and the destruction. Hoping humanitarian aid will at least limit the hardships in the coming weeks, months, but given the current situation, even before the earthquakes, it‚Äôs hard to believe it will be enough, as foreign funds dry up.
¬†
Seyad Aab, Zenda jan, Herat. 10.14.23. With @iomafghanistan

We are in interesting times. Lines are being drawn, conflicts arise. You know we live in one of the most peaceful times in the world on a global scale compared to our past. But things seem more Chaotic than ever. 

You check the news, shooting. You check social media, a conflict has sparked, but none of them started a few days ago, they are fires that burned a little too steadily, with a little too much tension and fuel, for clearly a little too long. The world is called upon to react, emotionally, non sensibly, in a very dogmatic and tribal sense. But this is our nature isn‚Äôt it, our history, as it cycles through different tribes, empires, and peoples. 

Many things are uncertain, but one thing is for sure. If you are not going to feel the heat of the fire yourself, try not to add any fuel to it from a distance. You won‚Äôt be the one getting burned. It is a responsibility upon you to look at the big picture as much as you can, to learn, to read, to listen more than you speak perhaps, especially from those you‚Äôve never heard the perspective of before. 

Whether you wish to fight, or make peace, or understand the issue at hand. In all three cases, you most know your enemy. And even more importantly, Ask why you call him such a term. 

If you‚Äôre going to speak on enemies, moral ‚Äúevils‚Äù, and things you choose to lower the value of in your language, you best be willing to back up that talk with some risk, some courage, and some suffering. God loves a passionate man, but has less to praise in an emotional one. Learn the distinction. Choose to think logically in a time of rapid emotions. 

And so if you choose to fight, make sure it is for good reasons, good cause, and train hard, give your enemies hell, and be willing to suffer for what you believe. This is what we must demand of ourselves. 

And if not, do what you can, speak the truth, aim for peace, and speak up for those with no voice. In the meantime, pray for the peace and prepare for war, peace is possible, but it never lasts forever. May God favor the brave and bless the martyrs, and give us one ounce of their bravery. I stand with the struggle.

In conflict, couples often get stuck in a scenario where they keep defending their own viewpoints and fighting to be right. They want their partner to agree with their side. 

Remember, your perception is your reality; your partner's perception is theirs. You are both right; each just looking at it from a different angle. 

On top of that, couples often blame each other and see the other as being wrong or being the problem, believing they themselves are right. 

Remember, your partner is not the problem; you are not the problem; the problem is the problem. It can help to realize that the problem lies outside of the couple and that you are both on the same team trying to solve the same problem. 

Stop the right-fighting because when one wins, you will both lose. It is about finding a win-win solution that will work well for both. 

It is about trying to understand each other's point of view and considering both viewpoints when trying to come to a solution that will work well for both.

Keep loving!
Des x

A U.S. State Department official announced his resignation Wednesday over the Biden administration's decision to send more arms to Israel as it carries out a massive assault on the occupied Gaza Strip, killing more than 3,400 people, decimating the enclave's civilian infrastructure, and strangling the population with an unlawful blockade.

"I cannot work in support of a set of major policy decisions, including rushing more arms to one side of the conflict, that I believe to be shortsighted, destructive, unjust, and contradictory to the very values that we publicly espouse, and which I wholeheartedly endorse: a world built around a rules-based order, a world that advances both equality and equity, and a world whose arc of history bends towards the promise of liberty, and of justice, for all," Josh Paul, who spent 11 years as director of congressional and public affairs for the U.S. State Department's Bureau of Political-Military Affairs, wrote in his resignation letter.

Paul helped oversee the transfer of U.S. weaponry to allies, a position that he acknowledged "was not without its moral complexity and moral compromises."

"I made myself a promise that I would stay for as long as I felt the harm I might do could be outweighed by the good I could do," Paul wrote. "In my 11 years I have made more moral compromises than I can recall, each heavily, but each with my promise to myself in mind, and intact. I am leaving today because I believe that in our current course with regards to the continued‚Äîindeed, expanded and expedited‚Äîprovision of lethal arms to Israel‚ÄîI have reached the end of that bargain."

Paul's resignation came hours after U.S. President Joe Biden embraced Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Tel Aviv and "reiterated his steadfast support for Israel" even as United Nations experts, human rights organizations, and international law scholars accuse the country of committing egregious war crimes‚Äîincluding genocide.

have you ever been sitting in a meeting, fully focused on what is being said, when suddenly, the small being that lives inside your body kicks you square in the bladder--completely catching you off guard--so that you pee just a little bit?

this is a daily experience for me at the moment, and i weirdly love the challenge of keeping a straight face while something so intense is happening to me somatically. let's be honest, i would LOVE to be able to pause the meeting to talk about it, but i hardly think society [as a whole] is ready to embrace bodies as a part of our human experience. 

part of the hustle culture of capitalism requires us to maintain a pace that diminishes the unique experience of each of our bodies.. whether we're talking about disability, mental health, chronic pain, injury, pregnancy, etc.. the implicit expectation put on the individual is 'just keep producing, and if something is 'wrong', then handle the symptoms with a pharmaceutical and then get back to producing'.

but i'm not here to soap box about disembodied living in america.. (or am i?)

speaking of changing bodies.. i have somehow managed to make it through my pregnancy without buying any new clothes. i've been enjoying hand-me-downs and also renting from @armoire.style ‚Äî they have an incredible range of styles and sizes, including an entire maternity range, and have a super user-friendly clothing rental subscription. they're also WOC-owned! win/win/win.

also, it feels important to name the conflict going on in the world at the moment, and how it is impacting each of us in various ways. i saw a stat that said that 5,522 pregnant people are expected to deliver in the next month in gaza, and that number is separate to how many babies and children are already in the middle east and involved. the grief is real, the divided opinions are real, the information fatigue is real. take care of yourself and stay offline as much as you need to. our bodies and nervous systems are not made to consume this much conflict and tragedy--and social media does not allow for humanity and nuance, both things we so desperately need. x

For the wounded, injured and sick in Gaza, there is seemingly no escape. On October 17, 2023, news broke that at least 500 patients, staff and people seeking shelter from Israeli bombs had been killed in an explosion at a hospital, according to health authorities in the Hamas-run enclave.

It amounts to a devastating loss of life during a campaign of bombing that has not spared the frail or sick. Just days earlier, the World Health Organization said in a stark assessment that an order to evacuate from hospital beds and head south amounts to a ‚Äúdeath sentence.‚Äù

By that time, four hospitals had already ceased functioning in Gaza‚Äôs north because of damage from Israeli bombs.

Beyond the sheer immediate devastation of the current conflict ‚Äì in which thousands of Israelis and Palestinians have been killed ‚Äì there will be significant and undoubtedly long-lasting implications for the Gaza Strip‚Äôs health system.

As a Palestinian expert in global health who has worked with medical professionals from Gaza, I know that even before this latest escalation of violence, health services in Gaza were in a poor shape. Insufficiently and poorly resourced for decades, doctors and hospitals also had to contend with the devastating effects of a 16-year blockade imposed by Israel, in part with coordination with Egypt.

‚ÄòThe war galloped across Luxembourg and came to a halt at the frontier.‚Äô

In the autumn of 1944, Lee Miller was following the liberation of Luxembourg for what would be an in-depth seven-page spread in both English and American Vogue. With her trusty Rollieflex camera in hand, Lee‚Äôs photographs from this time became emblematic of her journalism ‚Äì documenting the impact of conflict on civilian life. 

Here at the archives, we‚Äôve been pouring over Lee‚Äôs original draft manuscripts and correspondence. ‚ÄòThis is a very difficult piece you have sent me,‚Äô Lee wrote to her editor, Audrey Withers, ‚ÄòI‚Äôll try to put it all together for you into some sort of visual piece because it is harrowing.‚Äô Lee writes of bundles stacked in doorways ‚Äòbeing passed out of windows, falling off ridiculous carts‚Äô such as this one. 

In October 1944, Lee wrote to the censor, pleading for the material to be censored ‚Äòin advance so that I don‚Äôt break my heart and bore you with things that are un-releasable?‚Äô Sections of the article were scored through by the censor, and the story was eventually passed for publication in December.

A culmination of years of strategy and sacrifice for a moment that changed the world, on October 19, 1781, General George Washington accepted the surrender of British General Lord Charles Cornwallis at Yorktown, Virginia, effectively ending the military conflict of the American Revolution. When the war began six years earlier at the Battle of Lexington and Concord, few could have foreseen that the American colonists could defeat the powerful British Army and Navy.

In  the fall of 1781, the war was still in doubt. The British forces were divided with one army holding New York City and the other maneuvering through the southern colonies. A timely alliance brought the addition of French troops to the side of the Continental Army. Washington initially wanted to attack the British force in New York, but now supported by the French, he seized on the opportunity to move against Cornwallis‚Äôs army near Yorktown, Virginia. While the Continental Army marched south, a fleet of French ships was ordered to the area to cut off the British escape from the Chesapeake Bay. 

After combining his army with troops already around Yorktown under the command of Marquis de Lafayette, Washington began bombarding the British trenches on October 9. By October 17, Cornwallis realized he could no longer hold his position. Two days later, he signed the Articles of Capitulation, surrendering his troops to Washington on October 19. While the treaty ending the war was not signed for two more years, Cornwallis‚Äôs surrender represented the ultimate victory for the colonists and ensured American independence. 

The Washington Monument on the National Mall honors the military success of George Washington, as well as his later contributions in shaping our young nation and serving as our first president. The tallest building in the world when it was completed, it symbolizes a daring endeavor carefully achieved through patience, determination, and skill ‚Äì just like the birth of our nation.

Over the past two weeks, I've been looking closely at my own child, our surroundings, and life and it feels RARE. With 400+ million kids living in war/conflict zones around the world, including all the affected innocent children caught up in Israel/Gaza, it feels like a rarity to see a child growing up without fear of violence, abuse, neglect, or food insecurity.

And even among the kids who ARE at risk, we still see their unwavering optimism. We see kids in refugee camps, amidst an imminent threat of violence, still playing soccer, doing handstands, laughing, and smiling as they talk about their dreams of attending school and eating endless sugary baked goods.

I literally have no idea where I'm going with this but I feel grateful, helpless, guilty, optimistic, anxious, and lost all at the same time. And that's normal. Take time to be vulnerable and open about it.

May we do what we can to protect and preserve the unrelenting optimism of our children.

Celebrating 10 Years Married to @clairegraham01 

Did I ever think the girl I threw out of a nightclub one Sunday evening 14 years ago would be my wife? Lol

Lessons‚Ä¶

1. Share a vision. If you‚Äôre not clear on where you want to go TOGETHER, you'll drift apart.

Plan your goals together, both business + personal.

We have a weekly mastermind together every Sunday morning to stay aligned & communicate what's working Vs. What's not.

2. Avoid Stubbornness. It's a relationship killer.

When we disagree (almost daily, lol), we strive for win-win outcomes ASAP.

The real magic of your life lies in what you‚Äôre thinking but not saying. 

^Read that again

Moralüëá
Clear the air.
Keep moving forward!

3. Understand your partner's point of view before opening your mouth. This will expand your awareness & make you an all-around better human.

4. Know each other's schedules. We share calendars so we know what we're up to. This helps with planning & time management.

5. Conflict is normal. 

Avoiding conflict is unrealistic & will set you up for failure.

When things get boring or frustrating (which they will) - communicate it. 

Don‚Äôt sit & complain. Do something about it! 

We love a good debate, lol. It helps us understand each other + always has a silver lining that serves us.

6. Men, pick up your boxers & socks always or prepare to meet DOOM!

7. Give your partner time to think, have fun, & recharge by themselves. These serve as breathing spaces.

I go shooting and fishing, don‚Äôt look at my phone for hours on end.

Claire likes to do CrossFit, shop, and go out with the girls.

Strategic time + space apart is important.

8. Never piss off one of the sisters, lol.

9. Dial in your social circle. 

Get in the proximity of role models & interesting couples doing great things.

Be ruthless with who you let into your circle.

10. Date night every week.

The first thing I plan every week is fun. I then build my other commitments around it.

- Kids minded
- Phones off
- Set an intention to connect on a deeper level & escape the noise

Your partner is one of the most important people in your life. Serve them & make sure they serve you.

Grateful for you Mrs Graham

Wild Diversity started as a dream. Over the years this dream has blossomed into a vision where BIPOC and LGBTQ+ communities have belonging and freedom in the outdoors. Where any member of our community can see themselves out in nature radiating with joy. That vision is what we strive for every day as we work to create opportunities for interpersonal connection and deeper relationships to the outdoors. 

As an organization that believes in this dream, it is heartbreaking to witness the occupation that has been taking place for the last 75 years in Palestine. We are left speechless as we watch our Palestinian friends, family and community fight for their most basic rights and for their lives. We cannot stay silent. 

To our friends and community, we want to make it irrevocably clear that we stand with you. We stand with Palestine. 

What the world is currently witnessing is not a conflict, it is genocide and ethnic cleansing. We know that if we wish to see our dream of a world full of liberation, joy, diversity, and acceptance come true then we must fight for our community and stand against all types of injustice. 

We urge our community to come together during this time. Embrace your loved ones, mourn  these losses, and fight for our collective dream of liberation. 

Free Palestine.

When I checked my messages the other day, I noticed that my employees were engaged in something many of us dread: an argument.

I was drawn to this because, honestly, hindi ko talaga gusto yung feeling nung tension when there is a conflict, regardless if it's happening to me or any other person. I preferred everything to be peaceful because deep inside I thought that anything that produces unpleasant emotions like disagreements were a bad thing.

I can blame two things here:

1Ô∏è‚É£ My misunderstanding of the Law of Attraction (dapat daw positive lang)

2Ô∏è‚É£ My tendency to people please para happy happy lahat

Then, things changed when I read the book "The Five Dysfunctions of a Team" not long ago. 

It made me realize that healthy debates about ideas were actually a good sign for a team (team here can refer to family, friends, co-workers, intimate relationship, etc)

.. and that lack of conflict is a red flag.

Why?

Kasi hindi naman lahat sa team ay 100% agree sa sinasabi ng isa't isa. So kung walang sign ng conflict, it may mean that team members are not voicing their opinions and, in a sense, just tolerating each other.

And this bad habit of withholding our opinions to avoid conflict is where resentment often grows, and it is usually the cause of losing respect for one another in the long run. Soon, we'll find that we don't want to listen to or value that person's input anymore.

Even worse, we might find ourselves saying bad things about this person to others (even unintentionally) because we can't openly express our views within the team. Instead of addressing issues together, we share them with outsiders. This is often how the #UnproductiveMarites culture develops. üôÖ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

So what did I do when I saw this happening to my people the other day?

I spoke up.

Umepal ako.

I interrupted.

But not for my usual reason of stopping them because I want everyone to be happy happy.

But to tell them that what they're doing is good for the team, and that they need to keep it up. ü§†

That's when I realized that I had changed. 

That once again.. 

.. I had leveled up by a couple of points and become a better leader. üöÄ

It‚Äôs difficult to focus on anything outside of the Israeli genocide attempts in Gaza today, but actually the impulses of domination and resistance are universal and once we believe the lie that any one life matters less than another, the through-line is clear.

Grateful to journalists like Patricia for their courage and dedication to the truth.

Holding Space for Activated Parts
As tragedies and violence unfold in the Middle East, we would like to acknowledge and hold space for the grief, terror and anger being felt by Israelis, Palestinians, and those among the diaspora in our communities and around the world. 

The world is demanding much from everyone right now ‚Äì and an unimaginable amount is being asked of the caretakers and peacemakers in the region. We know they are there. We know they need support. In an effort to support those directly impacted by the conflict, and those who are holding space for those impacted by the conflict, we would like to offer the following meditation (link in bio) acknowledging and supporting parts that are struggling at this very difficult time.

Next week we will hold our annual conference, and it will be in person for the first time since 2019.  While we are looking forward to being together as a community, we also know that those who may need this community the most may not be able to attend.  We will dedicate time to sending Self energy to those who need it and who are not physically present with us.

The Institute is connecting with our partners in exploration of additional ways we can provide support. We are also open to suggestions from our community for how to best support groups who are working to support each other and those they work with during this time. The Jamaican Government Faces Scrutiny for Deporting Haitian Asylum Seekers Amid Ongoing Conflict - The Jamaican government is under scrutiny after a third group of Haitians, who arrived on the island on Sunday, were repatriated to Haiti, a nation currently facing an ongoing war. 

Just hours after another group of Haitians sought refuge on Jamaican shores in Portland, they were promptly placed on a boat and sent back to their homeland. These Haitians, who have the right to legal representation, reportedly had limited communication with attorneys.

According to international human rights lawyer Malene Alleyne, she was at the gate of the property where the refugees were held and attempted to present an asylum request to the authorities, as requested by one of the 35 Haitians. However, Alleyne was denied access to the property.

My Dear,

There is ongoing global trauma and conflict. Some days are dark and can create a sense of hopelessness.

I want to remind you that you can still choose to nourish yourself.

You have permission to be informed because you have compassion, but not over exposed.

You have permission to release the judgement you may feel from yourself and others about how you‚Äôre responding.

You have permission to tap into the energy of human connection, joy, peace, and the sacredness of now without guilt or shame.

My heart and body feel the weight of what is happening in the world. There are ways to care deeply without being consumed by the news and overwhelmed by anxiety.

Give yourself a soft landing by being gentle with yourself and others during this time.

Said with love,

Tosin

STOP THE WAR ON CHILDREN

Save the Children Philippines stands with the Philippine government and civil society in condemning the killing of civilians, including children, along with attacks on schools, hospitals, and public places in the ongoing Israel-Palestine conflict. This is a grave violation of human rights and children‚Äôs rights, and we collectively call for those responsible to be held to account for their actions.

In the middle of this, children are always the most vulnerable and first to suffer in any conflict. With every airstrike, rocket, and bullet fired, children‚Äôs sense of security is ripped away yet again, with dire consequences for their long-term wellbeing.

They are terrified, have been forced from their homes, and are cut off from an education. If violence escalates further, children‚Äôs lives and futures will be the inevitable cost. The only way to truly protect children‚Äôs lives is to halt this violence.

We therefore plead with our world leaders and actors on the ground to prioritize the preservation of human life above all else. Anything less will forever be a stain on our collective conscience.

Children must be protected at all times. Stop the war on children.

The Ultimate Confrontation: The Flower and the Bayonet 

It‚Äôs one of my favourite stories of design born from strife, hope and inspiration.

The first series of images from 1967 shows a young woman Jan Rose Kasmir, then a high school student, brazen enough to go and stare down bayonets and proffer a chrysanthemum to hostile soldiers. The photograph was taken by the famous Marc Riboud in Washington where over 100000 activists turned up to protest against the American occupation of Vietnam.
 
The second last image taken by American Bernie Boston the photo titled ‚ÄòFlower Power‚Äô 1967 was nominated  for the Pulitzer and shows a young man sticking flowers in gun nozzles. 

Both images became iconic and in 1999, Odile Lobadowsky, president of Kenzo Parfums, was inspired by Riboud‚Äôs picture and created a perfume bottle that was bayonet inspired with a lone flower inside. 

In the words of Namwali Serpell, ‚Äú‚Äòa flower stronger than a gun.‚Äô As maestro perfumer Alberto Morillas concocted the fragrance, the concept was refined: a red flower in the city, growing against a backdrop of skyscrapers and asphalt, both delicate and resilient. Kenzo introduced it in 2000 as Flower, a reminder that the autumnal day at the Pentagon three-plus decades earlier must have had a smell. Flower‚Äôs glass bottle is slender as a rifle barrel, but curved and yielding, a long-stemmed poppy seeming to float inside it. It‚Äôs so tall that stores have to display it lying on its side. The perfume smells like no particular flower and like every flower in the world combined. The marketing materials read, ‚ÄúNo one plants or chooses me. I simply grow.‚Äù ‚Ä¶‚Äù (BIDOUN)

And so as our worlds turn again to the guns, it‚Äôs your choice to be the flower and choose hope.

Posted @withregram ‚Ä¢ @happystrokes.in The power of pause lies in its ability to bring clarity, reflection, and a sense of control to our actions and words. Taking a moment to pause can help us make more deliberate and thoughtful decisions, fostering better communication and understanding in various situations.

The benefits of incorporating pauses in your life include:

1. Improved decision-making: Pausing allows you to think more clearly and make well-considered choices.

2. Better communication: Pauses help you listen actively and respond thoughtfully in conversations.

3. Stress reduction: Taking a moment to pause can lower stress levels and promote relaxation.

4. Enhanced creativity: Pauses provide space for new ideas and insights to emerge.

5. Increased self-awareness: Pausing allows for introspection and self-reflection.

6. Conflict resolution: It helps prevent impulsive reactions in conflicts, leading to more productive resolutions.

7. Health benefits: Pausing can reduce anxiety and improve overall well-being.

8. Time management: It aids in prioritizing tasks and staying focused on what's important.

9. Improved relationships: Pauses enable empathy and understanding in interactions with others.

10. Mindfulness and presence: Pausing promotes being fully present in the moment, leading to a more fulfilling life.

"What does the concept of 'pausing' mean to you, and how has it impacted your life? Share a moment when taking a pause made a significant difference. #PowerOfPause"

‚ÄúIsrael has a right to defend itself.‚Äù It is a refrain frequently invoked to justify Israeli responses to attacks launched against its citizens by Palestinian militants. Yet not every Israeli has accepted that truism. Indeed, if there is a single individual who best represents the challenge to such thinking it is the late Yeshayahu Leibowitz.

A fierce embodiment of the Socratic gadfly, Leibowitz (1903-1994) was unafraid to use strong language to criticize Israel‚Äôs occupation of the Palestinian people and territories, which commenced in 1967.

‚ÄúThe corruption characteristic of every colonial regime would also prevail in the State of Israel,‚Äù he said in his typically provocative style. For Leibowitz, the occupation meant that Israel forfeited its right to retaliate in self-defense, and he was ever vocal about this position. For his opinions, he was called by no less an eminence than Sir Isaiah Berlin ‚Äúthe conscience of Israel.‚Äù Revisiting Leibowitz‚Äôs views now‚Äîmore than five decades after he first articulated them‚Äîprovides observers with a unique, and often overlooked, perspective in contemporary discourse on the conflict.

Yeshayahu Leibowitz was born in Riga, Latvia in 1903 into a family of religious Jews. They were Zionists, adherents of the pan-national movement founded in Europe whose goal was to establish a sovereign state for the Jewish people in their historical homeland, namely, the land of Israel. A brilliant pupil, Leibowitz studied chemistry and philosophy at the University of Berlin, and then medicine in Koln and Heidelberg, before moving to Basel to finish his medical degree while the Nazis rose to power in Germany. In 1934, he immigrated to Palestine and took an appointment as a professor of biochemistry, and later neurophysiology, at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, where he taught for nearly six decades. In addition to publishing numerous books and articles on everything from the history of science to the philosophy of Maimonides, he was the editor of the Encyclopedia Hebraica, and a frequent public speaker on Jewish thought, ethics, and philosophy.

Read more in ‚ÄúRevisiting Yeshayahu Leibowitz‚Äù by Moti Mizrahi. Link in bio.

A Nairobi trader has claimed that Nairobi county council officers, also known as Kanjos, robbed her of Ksh400,000 at Mwariro Market along Ring Road.

The lady, who sells potatoes in bulk, alleged that she lost all the cash she had made in sales and was counting huge losses after Kanjo raided her shop. 

Furthermore, the officers allegedly manhandled her, took the Ksh400,000 cash from her pocket, and nearly snatched her phone during the incident that happened on the evening of Wednesday, October 18. 

The woman attributed the raid to a misunderstanding between the county officials and the market management, adding that the traders ended up bearing the brunt. 

''There is a possible conflict between the county council officials and market directors that has caught traders in between,'' she alleged but did not divulge whether the directors reached out to the traders to clarify the issue. 

She also did not clarify if she had filed a report with the police in an effort to recover her Ksh400,000 cash. 

Nonetheless, the lady further complained that she is charged a Ksh 9,000-10,000 fee before she accesses the market, based on the capacity of potatoes she transports from the farm to her shop. 

Other than the frustrations by the kanjos, traders selling perishable goods complained of high cess fees imposed by the county government. 

They also urged the county, led by Governor Johnson Sakaja, to intervene and resolve the crisis by enacting better management structures and reducing taxes. 

Earlier on Wednesday, smokie and egg vendors at the Nairobi CBD counted losses after Nairobi Kanjos confiscated their trollies. The county council askaris alleged that the vendors were operating without licenses. 

Later on, Governor Sakaja condemned the act, apologised and compensated the vendors Ksh 10,000 each.

The Osage Nation is an indigenous American tribe that formed around the Ohio Valley over two thousand years ago and migrated south after being hit by European diseases and frequent conflict with the Iroquois in the 17th and 18th centuries. 

In Oklahoma they purchased a reservation on the Kansas border, covering an area of roughly 5,900 square kilometres.

In 1894, vast oil reserves were discovered, by the 1920's bringing in $65,000 per head and a wave of extreme corruption with dozens of murders, only ended by congress disallowing non-native Osage from inheriting deeds to oil reserves. This infamous spate of killings is explored in Martin Scorsese‚Äôs new film.

Oil production peaked and now 90% of the Nation's budget comes from gambling. The Osage Nation is living in relative prosperity. Though most members are Catholics, they continue to honour ancestral traditions and original beliefs. 

1. Members of the Osage Nation take part in a commemoration ceremony for the anniversary Osage Nation recognition on 11 March 2006. 

2. An illuminated sign at the Osage Nation Visitors Center in Pawhuska.

3. Artist Wendy Ponca in her home with her children Sarah and Tom, her husband Antony and her adopted children Jade and Clovis. 

4. Bison grazing in the Tall Grass Prairie Reserve.

5. Everett Waller, Chairman of the Board of Mineral Resources including Petroleum standing in front of a mural featuring people from the Osage Nation.

6. A swimming pool at the Hotel Casino Osage. 97% of the Osage Nation's income comes from casinos. The Hotel Casino Osage is the biggest.

7. Commemoration ceremony for the anniversary Osage Nation recognition.

8. A man kneels and prays during Sunday Mass in a Catholic Church whose congregation comes from both the Native American Osage Nation and the local white American community.

9. An art work in Hominy City, home to many Native Americans from the Osage Nation.

More often than not, it‚Äôs not big events that cause a relationship to break down. Instead, it‚Äôs a repeating cycle of negative reactions to perceived threats. These behaviors were once protective to us as children, but as adults, they‚Äôre damaging to our relationships.

These threats might look different for the different attachment styles: For those with an anxious attachment style, indications of disinterest, disengagement, or lack of physical affection may trigger fears of abandonment‚Äìso they fight against this threat by creating conflict, pushing for attention, or acting clingy to reduce their anxiety.

Those with an avoidant attachment style may perceive emotional closeness, attempts at intimacy, and having to open up as threats to their individuality‚Äìso they may flee from this threat and their feelings of anxiety by shutting down and withdrawing.

People with a disorganized attachment style often see emotional closeness as both desirable and fear-inducing‚Äìresulting in frequently swapping between both flighting for and fleeing from it. Their anxiety is difficult to manage because their attachment needs were consistently shifting as children, so they‚Äôve transitioned their anxiety-reducing behaviors to their adult relationships.

But by‚Ä¶
- Identifying the problem
- Questioning how your life would be different in you changed these behaviors
- Understanding the role of your attachment style in the cycle
- Working on communication skills, and
- Staying motivated
‚Ä¶it is possible to break the insecure relationship cycle!

On Tuesday night an explosion at the Al-Ahli hospital in Gaza killed an unknown number of people. From that moment two irreconcilable accounts of what caused the blast started to diverge.‚Å†
‚Å†
Whatever else happened it was a human tragedy and an object lesson in the power of misinformation to distort reality and influence real events:‚Å†
‚Å†
üî≥ Hamas quickly blamed an Israeli airstrike and said up to 471 people had died. ‚Å†
üî≥ Israel denied responsibility, blaming a misfired rocket launched by Palestinian Islamic Jihad. ‚Å†
üî≥ By that time a summit aimed at containing the war had been cancelled. Yesterday pro-Palestinian demonstrations filled city centres across the Middle East.‚Å†
üî≥ When two sides in a conflict trade blame and social media blurs the lines between citizen journalism and propaganda, how can independent researchers pick their way towards the truth? ‚Å†
‚Å†
It‚Äôs not impossible. Minute analysis of raw footage uploaded to social media ‚Äì in this case mainly Telegram ‚Äì can provide a basis for sorting fact from fiction.‚Å†
‚Å†
Yesterday researchers at Bellingcat, a pioneer of open source intelligence (Osint), were going frame-by-frame through more than 50 videos and images of the explosion and its aftermath.‚Å†
‚Å†
They were looking for clues to: The type of weapon that might have caused it; where it came from; where it landed; and its blast radius.‚Å†
‚Å†
They found plenty, but certain aspects of this new nadir in Israeli-Palestinian history were already clear.‚Å†
‚Å†
Both sides lie. Recent examples include Israel‚Äôs claim last year its soldiers didn‚Äôt kill the journalist Shireen Abu-Akleh ‚Äì disproved by open-source intelligence within days ‚Äì and a Hamas claim last week not to have targeted civilians on 7 October. But, with patience, the platforms that spread misinformation can be used to expose it too.‚Å†

text: NSW Jewish Board of Deputies responds to the NSW Teachers Federation‚Äôs (@teachersfed) statement on the Middle East conflict.

The First Day of Peace üïäÔ∏è 

A day so many all over long for. It hurts to even think about it. But for us to find peace we must sit with the discomfort, not be complacent and actively work towards justice whether it‚Äôs on a global scale or small acts in your community, in your friend circles. 

In this beautiful story, the mountain people and valley people live separately. When the extreme weather causes the river that runs through their town to dry out, the two must come together. They try and it ends in fighting. The winter comes and both parties are able to retrieve water and remain separate. The seasons change again this time bringing an over-abundance of rain with the warming temperatures. It floods the valley. Children of the mountain decide that they must do something to help their neighbors stuck in the floods. They bring them food, supplies and necessities. The valley people gratefully reciprocate with gifts. A new day, a new peace is born with two peoples who had only known how to fight with each other until that moment. 

This book shines light on disagreements between two groups of people, the valley and mountain peoples. I was blown away by the beautiful commentary on conflict and bigotry. It showed the children stepping up to break the cycles of othering, separation and hate that tends to get passed down.  This book challenges young people to look at conflict through a compassionate lens. 

This book was submitted as a contender for #bookstagang_bestof2023 

I‚Äôve linked it to my profile and stories.

It is truly heartbreaking to witness such a catastrophic event unfold right before our very eyes and to feel helpless and guilty for living a normal and comfortable life whilst our brothers and sisters on the other side of the world are suffering. 

Many nations, businesses and brands are taking a neutral stance in regards to the ongoing atrocity and genocide happening in Gaza, not realizing that to be neutral is to be complacent. As Desmond Tutu said ‚ÄúIf you are neutral in situations of injustice, you have chosen the side of the oppressor‚Äù

How can we be neutral when thousands of civilians, mostly children are being brutally killed everyday.

We refuse to remain neutral when an ethnic cleansing is happening to the Palestinian people. 

We refuse to be neutral when there is a genocide happening right before our eyes.

We stand with the Palestinian people and hope that they are granted ease.

Reposted @yuval_noah_harari We must win this war of souls. In its war against Hamas, Israel has a duty to defend its territory and its citizens, but it must also defend its humanity. Our war is with Hamas, not with the Palestinian people. Palestinian civilians deserve to enjoy peace and prosperity in their homeland, and even in the midst of conflict their basic human rights should be recognized by all sides. This refers not only to Israel, but also to Egypt, which shares a border with the Gaza Strip, and which has partially sealed that border. Right now, the minds of both Israelis and Palestinians are filled to the brim with their own pain: no space is left to even acknowledge the pain of the other side. But outsiders who are not themselves immersed in pain should make an effort to empathize with all suffering humans, rather than lazily seeing only part of the terrible reality. It is the job of outsiders to help maintain a space for peace.

This isn't the actual quote of Catholic author and philosopher G.K. Chesterton. His actual words were: 

‚ÄúWe do not really want a religion that is right where we are right. What we want is a religion that is right where we are wrong.‚Äù¬†The Catholic Church and Conversion

First, a point of agreement. Both Protestants (for the most part) and Catholics believe in one God, one Lord Jesus Christ, one Holy Spirit, one faith (the Gospel), and one baptism. Jesus also built¬†one Church, not two, three, or three-thousand‚Äîone. Initially made up of the Apostles and their followers, this Church spread throughout the world. Due to the great distances, and to preserve the message of Christ, members of the Church wrote letters (epistles), accounts of Jesus‚Äô life (the Gospels), and the history of the early Church (Acts). In turn, these writings were copied and shared among the Church in different locations.

Almost immediately, the young Church had to address error. A group known as Judaizers, Jewish Christians who taught that Gentile converts to Christianity become Jews first (through circumcision) and follow the Mosaic Law, caused conflict even among¬†St. Peter and St. Paul. Eventually, the Council of Jerusalem settled the matter and¬†sent a letter¬†of explanation to the whole Church. Thus, the Church, under the guidance of the Holy Spirit, instituted an authoritative paradigm to address significant errors that pose significant threats to the unity of Christ‚Äôs one Church.

Moreover, the tendency to err did not cease with the Judaizers and the Council of Jerusalem. As the Church matured and its theology grew more complex, errors also emerged to divide Christ‚Äôs one Church.¬†Examples: Docetism¬†(1st¬†century),¬†Montanism,¬†Ebionites¬†(Adoptionism),¬†Valentinianism,¬†Sabellianism,¬†Marcionism,¬†Patripassianism¬†(2nd¬†century),¬†Novatianism¬†(3rd¬†century),¬†Arianism,¬†Donatism,¬†Monophysitism,¬†Apollinarism¬†(4th¬†century),¬†Nestorianism,¬†Pelagianism,¬†Eutychianism, (5th¬†century),¬†Iconoclasm, and¬†Monothelitism¬†(7th¬†century). 

Many of the errors (heresies) above required¬†ecumenical councils¬†as a means of correction. Jesus established one Church. (Read more below)

With a stone we can hurt others or build walls. And with the same stone, we can build a shelter to protect those same people. I express my absolute rejection of any policy that violates the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. I stand in solidarity with all those who at this moment do not have light, water, shelter and food. Today I feel neither satisfied to be European nor human. I wish I could do something more meaningful than signing online petitions and posting this. I wish I had political power as a leader of a government to stop a genocide, without getting entangled in diplomatic concessions. I wish I possessed a large fortune to donate to help the victims of war. Humans today are asked to manage our anger and frustration with techniques and therapy; society invites us to be better, tolerant, sensitive and empathetic citizens. I‚Äôve been thinking long and hard about how I can contribute to this moment. Something more than attending protests and discussing online. And, how to do so without replicating resources that already exist. 

There is a long shared history of solidarity between the Palestinian struggle and Black communities and over the next few weeks I will do my best to break down how these came about and why.

As this conflict escalates I‚Äôm increasingly concerned about rise in antisemitism and Islamophobia. When you are interacting online please see people as people first. And let us be careful about slipping into tropes and stereotypes that have historically been used to oppress both these groups for generations.

Most of us are privileged by distance and with that we must prioritise empathy. Our elected leaders are gaslighting us and our media is polarised, we are seeing vastly different content on our feeds. We must allow people the opportunity to change their minds. 

Art is history.

#onthisdayinhistory Lord Cornwallis surrendered at Yorktown on October 19, 1781. By the early 1780s, the United States gained greater assistance from foreign nations, especially France. With their assistance, American forces were able to launch successful attacks on British positions and gradually regain control of the US. By this stage of the American Revolution, most of the fighting was taking place in Virginia as many of the northern cities were recaptured by the Americans. 

The Siege of Yorktown used a combined arms tactic to force a British surrender.  By land, forces under the command of George Washington and the Marquis de Lafayette advanced to meet the British positions in Yorktown, commanded by Lord Cornwallis. By sea, a French fleet under the command of the Comte de Grasse surrounded Yorktown and prevented a British retreat by sea. A siege began in late September 1781, and on October 19, the British surrendered. 

The capture of Lord Cornwallis forced the British government to negotiate an end to the conflict. As such, the Battle of Yorktown would be the last major engagement in the American Revolution. The United State‚Äôs independence would be guaranteed by September 1783 with the Treaty of Paris. #siegeofyorktown #usa #uk #france

Do you like it if anyone disrespects you? I know it‚Äôs an absurd question. Of course, you don‚Äôt. No one is immune to the effects of disrespect. Most of us find it hard to shake off incidents where we feel we were not respected enough. 

Never put up with disrespectful behavior. If you accept disrespect at the beginning of any relationship, you will find yourself forever struggling to fix that aspect. How two people or new family members treat each other in the first few weeks of meeting pretty much sets the tone of that relationship for the rest of their lives.¬†It means there came a moment in your life when you stopped loving yourself, that moment when you let someone disrespect you simply because they could. It means you accepted that moment. There is very little hope of now getting respect from this person.

If you are going to accept disrespectful behavior today, tomorrow, it‚Äôll get worse. Therefore, if you love yourself and want any sense of peace and equality in your personal relationships, make it clear in no uncertain terms the respect you seek. If someone is shouting at you today, at the next conflict, they are not going to lower their decibel. If anything, it‚Äôll be higher. Put a stop to it right at the beginning, no matter what the price. Otherwise, the pattern will become: conflict -> argument -> disrespect -> distance -> apology -> repeat. This pattern creates excess baggage. 

In personal relationships, remember the golden rule: whatever negative behavior you accept even once will only worsen over time.
Ultimately, the least everyone deserves is respect. And the paradox is that it can‚Äôt be granted as such, it has to be earned. If you deserve respect but don‚Äôt get it, you must take charge of your life. On the other hand, no matter how much you dislike someone, never deprive them of respect, even if out of politeness. For, respect is an acknowledgment of your existence. And, that is a big deal, one of the most fundamental human needs.

Self-knowledge is true knowledge‚Äîall other knowledge changes. What we learn in school differs based on the period of time. Our school knowledge is not based on what's good for us but rather on the best way to govern and control others.

That's why some communities send their children to two schools‚Äîone to learn about others, the other to learn about themselves. So, with all that we think we know, such as the name of the first president, sadly, we don't know who we are. We've spent years believing in the intellect and not the spirit. As a result, we stay child-like, superficially smart, and uninvolved instead of wise and evolved.

With self-knowledge, we become empowered with thoughts that transcend this world. We seek that ultimate truth. But to seek that truth, we must realize the conflict within ourselves.

That conflict is to either remain asleep or wake up. Better yet, as the story goes, we can be like "Iai," an ass that won't let go of the lies or falsehood. Undoubtedly, we've become stubborn in thinking that the path is one of assimilation with a dominant force, whereas it's one of assimilating with a life force. No one will empower you with self-knowledge, which leads us to the "ultimate" truth. Give yourself the gift of waking up to truly being free. -Dr. Robbin Alston

"We have nothing against each other on a personal level. It is a political problem." Amjad Kaware, a Palestinian who has lived in Belgium since 2019, and the Jewish Jonath Weinberger testified together this morning in "The Seventh Day". Despite the bloody conflict raging between the Israelis and Hamas fighters, they agree on a possible solution to the conflict: "There must be moderate leaders at the table on both sides.

The conflict between the Israelis and the Hamas fighters continues unabated. There have already been many civilian casualties on both the Israeli and Palestinian sides. The sadness and fear about this also brought both sides together, this morning in "The Seventh Day".

Amjad Kaware grew up in Gaza. The Palestinian has lived in Belgium since 2019, but all his family still lives in Gaza. "The last video call was three days ago, since then I haven't heard from them because there is no more electricity. Their mobile phones are flat and they can't charge them. In the last conversation with my mother she said that there are simply no safe places in Gaza. So they stay at home, hoping that a bomb won't fall on their heads."

The last video call was three days ago, I haven't heard from them since

9-year-old son witnesses Hamas attack
Jewish Jonath Weinberger, who lives in Antwerp, also experienced anxious days. Two of her four children were in Israel when Hamas launched its surprise attack last weekend. Her son Levi, who was visiting family there with his dad, is now back home safe and sound. "He is doing well, he is calm, but he has been really scared."

5 Ways to Get a Conflict Conversation Back on Track

Agree: Find something your partner has said that you can agree with. Start your sentence with ‚ÄúI agree‚Äù, ‚ÄúI partially agree‚Äù, or ‚ÄúI agree and‚Äù.

Reinforce Team: Highlight that you are on the same team and it‚Äôs you two against the problem.

Take a  Break: Indicate you are too overwhelmed to continue and that you need a break to collect your thoughts.

Take Responsibility: Be accountable for the role you played in creating the problem.

Compromise: Find a solution that is not 100% of what either of you want, but honors most of both of your needs.

Our hearts break as we witness the crisis unfolding in Gaza and the surrounding areas. As a humanitarian organization, we are guided by the principles of humanity, neutrality, impartiality, and independence to deliver assistance to those most in need. Alight responds to emergencies where we are best positioned to provide immediate support and over the last 12 days, we have been continuously assessing the situation to determine how we may serve the communities impacted by the conflict. 

Within the last 24 hours, the humanitarian corridor into Gaza opened. This provides a critical avenue for aid into Gaza in order to deliver essential resources like water, food, and medicine. @un_ocha has reported that the total number of internally displaced people in Gaza is currently estimated at about one million. 

We are raising emergency funding on behalf of Alight's affiliate, @Questscope, and an alliance of trusted, local organizations who are providing humanitarian relief in the region. The alliance has already provided over 2,000 food baskets, set-up community street kitchens, and distributed fuel to hospitals in the southern region of Gaza. But they are in desperate need of more funding. 

We ask that you hold space for compassion and care for the countless lives that have been lost and affected in recent weeks and if possible, please consider making a donation. Link in bio.

Pakistan Thursday dispatched the first consignment carrying relief assistance to Gaza as Israel's indiscriminate bombardment continues on the Hamas-ruled strip, killing thousands and displacing millions.

The relief assistance, carrying one thousand winter tents, four thousand blankets, and three tonnes of medicines, will reach Palestine via Egypt in a chartered aircraft, the Foreign Office said in a statement.

Israel's unabated airstrikes on Gaza have claimed nearly 3,500 lives while thousands of others are injured. Entire city blocks have been levelled, water, food, and power have been cut off, and over one million people have been displaced.

üü† Wednesday was #nationalunityday and #NUFSD is U-Knighted against bullying! Black and Gold made way for orange at A. MacArthur Barr yesterday as several students, faculty, staff and administration members arrived wearing brightly colored shirts, pants and headbands to send a visible message that ‚Äúno child should ever experience bullying.‚Äù

October is recognized across the country as #NationalBullyingAwarenessMonth and ‚ÄòUnity Day‚Äô was created by @pacer_nbpc to ‚Äúunite for kindness, acceptance, and inclusion.‚Äù A perfect fit for #NUFSD, which has been developing MTSS (multi-tiered support systems) to maximize student achievement and support students social, emotional, and behavior needs from a strengths-based perspective.

‚ÄúThe middle school has been working on helping students develop an understanding of what it means to be part of a community, and how their words and actions impact the community.,‚Äù says Barr Principal Michelle O‚ÄôSullivan. ‚ÄúNational Unity Day focuses on promoting inclusion and kindness, so our SEL and Mental Health Committees worked together to plan age appropriate lessons and activities deigned to raise awareness and help call students to action!"

Students spent their homeroom periods discussing the difference between conflict, mean moments and bullying and the importance of knowing the difference between these situations. 

‚ÄúWe want them to recognize that acceptance and inclusion does not mean you have to be friends with everyone, but we can be friendly to everyone,‚Äú says School Psychologist Maryclare Farrington.

Students in the Better Together Club designed kindness posters with assistance from club leaders as well as Principal O‚ÄôSullivan and @clarkstownpd SRO Culianos. In addition to the posters, several other anti bullying messages will appear throughout the school. Outside the main office is a tree adorned with orange leaves that features positive sayings crafted by our sixth graders.

Thank you to the Barr faculty, Principal O‚ÄôSullivan, AP's Latoya Oates and Khris Arvanites, Deputy Superintendent Dr. Meredith Fox and the members of the SEL and Mental Health committees for making National Unity Day a success!

One of my favorite quotes from the Universal House of Justice states, ‚ÄúChildren are the most precious treasure a community can possess, for in them are the promise and guarantee of the future. To go to Israel, or not to go? And for what purpose? Emmanuel Macron has been weighing up the options and assessing the risks and rewards. 

The French president has been hesitating and getting ready at the same time, as Israel prepares to launch a ground offensive in Gaza. 

On the sidelines of his official visit to Albania on Tuesday, October 17, Macron conceded that he might visit the Jewish state "in the next few days" or "in the next few weeks." "My desire is to be able to travel [to Israel] when we can obtain a concrete agreement either on non-escalation, or on humanitarian issues and, more broadly, on everything," he said from Tirana.

A visit to Israel by Macron has been under consideration since the Hamas terrorist attacks on the Jewish state on October 7. But the possibility of such a presidential trip gained momentum on Monday, when it became apparent that first German Chancellor Olaf Scholz and subsequently US President Joe Biden, were preparing to visit the region, on Tuesday and Wednesday respectively. Since then, the British Prime Minister, Rishi Sunak, announced on Wednesday evening that he too would be visiting the region on Thursday.

Egyptian President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi's invitation for France to attend a conference on the future of the Palestinian cause on Saturday could have encouraged Macron to visit the Middle East, and thereby assert France's position ‚Äì which is somewhere between support for Israel against terrorism and concern for the Palestinian cause. But the Elys√©e Palace has been concerned that the summit would produce a communiqu√© condemning Israel.

Tweens have crushes, they fantasize, and they get aroused. Pretending these feelings don‚Äôt or shouldn‚Äôt exist is counterproductive. The conflict is in accepting this biological fact alongside a parental need to protect kids from being exposed to adult experiences for which they aren‚Äôt emotionally or physically prepared.
To effectively do this requires a deep examination of your fears. By asking yourself, ‚ÄúWhat am I most afraid of?‚Äù you can zero in on how to give your young adolescent advice and limits specific to your concern and not just issue blanket statements of disapproval. Your child needs direction from you, but they‚Äôll tune you out if you talk about dating like it‚Äôs a gateway to disaster. Keep your child‚Äôs interest by balancing the nos with yeses, fears with hopes, and negatives with positives.

‚ÄúWASHINGTON, D.C. ‚Äì Oregon‚Äôs U.S. Senator Jeff Merkley, joined by U.S. Senators Patty Murray (D-WA), Ron Wyden (D-OR), Maria Cantwell (D-WA), today urged the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) to reject a proposal from TC Energy for a major expansion of methane gas infrastructure in the Pacific Northwest, as FERC is scheduled to take up the proposal at a Thursday meeting. The Senators pointed to a myriad of problems with TC Energy‚Äôs proposal and FERC‚Äôs consideration process, including the proposal‚Äôs direct conflict with Washington, Oregon, and California climate laws; a potential rise in energy costs for consumers; TC Energy‚Äôs troubled safety record; and FERC‚Äôs failure to properly and sufficiently consult Tribes prior to a final decision. FERC is poised to make a decision despite the serious climate impacts of this project, which would undermine state climate laws and conflict with the Biden administration‚Äôs climate goals. FERC‚Äôs decision Thursday will prove to be a major litmus test on whether the Commission can pivot towards a clean energy future or whether it will continue to approve projects that are incompatible with avoiding the worst impacts of climate chaos. 

The Senators also raise concerns that FERC failed to properly consult with impacted Tribes, which is a trust obligation and raises questions about whether the proposal could impact tribal treaty rights. The Columbia River Inter-Tribal Fish Commission was not consulted as part of the environmental review of the project, despite the fact that the pipeline travels near the Snake River and a safety incident could potentially impact endangered fish. ‚Äú
